<FIRST>r w PM-ImpeachmentAmendment     09-23 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Impeachment Amendment,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Wants Supreme Court to Take Over Impeachment Trials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers who have been tied up by the
impeachment trials of three federal judges in as many years are
calling for a change in the Constitution to hand such trials to the
Supreme Court.
   Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., chairman of the 12-member trial
committee that heard the case of U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon
earlier this month, said Friday that he would propose a
constitutional amendment to relieve Congress of its impeachment
duties.
   ``They ought to be the ultimate triers of fact,'' Fowler said of
the Supreme Court justices.
   ``They are the most qualified. They have the constitutional
perspective on both the protections and sensitivity of federal
judgeships,'' he said.
   He said the justices also have more time for the lengthy process
required to remove judges from the federal bench.
   The amendment would pertain only to the federal judiciary,
leaving the trial of other public officials impeached by the House
to the Senate, said Fowler, who said he would sponsor the proposal
with Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
   An impeachment voted by the House serves as an indictment for
trial before the Senate. A two-thirds vote of the Senate is required
to then remove an official from office and disqualify the person
from holding other federal office.
   There only have been 15 impeachments by the House sent to the
Senate for trial in the 200-year history of the Congress, but three
of them have been in the last three years and all of the last three
were federal judges.
   Fowler said he spent all of August studying the Nixon case prior
to the four-day trial before his special 12-member committee earlier
this month. The full Senate is expected to take no less than two
days to hear the case, debate and vote.
   Senate hearings in the impeachment case against U.S. District
Judge Alcee Hastings of Florida took four weeks last summer and are
awaiting action by the full Senate.
   The impeachment and trial of U.S. District Judge Harry Claiborne
in 1986 took the committee 10 days to hear and the full Senate 18
hours to consider before voting to remove Claiborne from office.
According to Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., who was majority leader at the
time, the Senate floor proceedings took more time than all but a
handful of major issues before the 98th Congress.
   Under the Constitution, the federal judges are appointed for life
and can be removed from office only by voluntary resignation, death
or trial by Congress.
   Fowler's plan for a constitutional amendment is not the first
call for a change in the discipline of federal judges.
   Rep. Robert Kastenmeier, D-Wis., chairman of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on courts, intellectual property and the administration
of justice, has proposed strengthening federal laws governing the
judges and setting up a commission to study the impeachment process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
