<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Crack     09-23 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Crack,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Defends Arranged Crack Sale for Drug Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says it doesn't really matter
that a drug dealer was coaxed into selling crack cocaine near the
White House _ just so the president could tell the American people
that's where the sale took place.
   ``The man went there and sold drugs in front of the White House,
didn't he?'' the president told reporters in Maine on Friday.
``That's the bottom line. That's what the man did.''
   Bush's press secretary, Marlin Fitzwater, and the Drug
Enforcement Administration concede the drug dealer was maneuvered
into making a previously arranged sale in Lafayette Park, across the
street from the White House.
   The president displayed the cocaine in a see-through plastic bag
in his nationally televised drug strategy speech on Sept. 5. He told
the audience the crack had been ``seized a few days ago in a park
across the street from the White House.''
   A Democratic senator from Louisiana, John Breaux, criticized the
president's use of the prop as ``staged.''
   ``Is this really a drug war, or is this theatrics and
screenplay?'' he asked. ``We don't need the president to lure drug
pushers to Lafayette Park for photo opportunities.''
   And a reporter suggested to the president that the transaction
wouldn't have taken place in the park had the cocaine not been
needed for the speech.
   ``The message I get out of it (is) a man was busted in front of
the White House and I cannot feel sorry for him,'' Bush said. ``He
ought not to be out peddling these insidious drugs. It's ruining the
children of this country.''
   The president said he'd asked for a drug sample ``from that
vicinity to show it can happen anywhere ... and that's what they
gave me. And they told me where they caught this guy.''
   Bush spoke as if the suspected dealer, a teenager, had been
arrested. Although the transaction with an undercover DEA agent was
photographed, the dealer was not taken into custody, agents said,
because they hoped he would sell a larger amount later and identify
his organization.
   A planned arrest earlier this week fell through when the suspect
did not show up, and agents hope to obtain indictments against him.
   Asked if the American people were manipulated into thinking drugs
were being sold near the White House, Bush replied: ``What do you
mean it didn't really (happen)? The guy was arrested or grabbed for
selling drugs in front of the White House. It didn't exist? It
didn't happen?''
   On every drug bust, Bush said, ``You bring somebody someplace.''
   Bush became irritated with reporters' questions, gesturing toward
the press at one point and saying, ``I don't understand. Are these
advocates here for this drug guy?''
   But while Bush and Fitzwater defended the arrangement, another
senior White House official suggested the Drug Enforcement
Administration had been ``a little overzealous.''
   ``We told them that if a buy could be made near the White House,
so much the better. They took us literally,'' said the official,
asking not to be identified.
</TEXT>
