<FIRST>r a PM-BlessingFlap     09-23 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blessing Flap,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condo Resident Ordered to Dump `Bless This Home' Sign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frances Reiter can't figure out what's
offensive about the heart-shaped ``God bless this house'' sign on
the front door of her apartment, but her condominium board says it
has to go.
   Ms. Reiter, who has lived at the Fairways Riviera complex for 17
years, says she's been told to remove the sign by Monday.
   ``She is not supposed to put anything strange on her door,''
condo board member Theo Zeelander said Thursday.
   Ms. Reiter can't see what's wrong with her sign because other
residents decorate their doors with mezuzas _ Biblical inscriptions
in Hebrew meant to be hung on doorposts.
   ``Are we in America? I have every right to have that sign on my
door,'' Ms. Reiter said. ``I am a Christian. This is my religious
symbol asking God to bless my home.''
   Condo President Sidney Jacobs wouldn't explain why the
association found the sign offensive, but said it has to go.
   ``If the sign was somewhere else on another front door hidden
from view, it wouldn't matter, but her door is very close to the
condo's meeting room. A lot of people have to pass by her door, and
it's offensive to everyone,'' he said.
   Jacobs has sent a letter telling Ms. Reiter the condo association
would remove the sign if she does not. He said she was in violation
of a condo regulation that prohibits residents from decorating their
front doors.
   Ms. Reiter said she has called a lawyer and is ready to go to
court.
   ``If they pull down that sign, there will be trouble,'' she said.
</TEXT>
