<BYLINE>Names in the News</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rolling Stones may not seem like
publicity-shy types, but they banned reporters and photographers
from a newspaper whose shutterbug snapped a few unauthorized shots
during a concert.
   The photographer from the Herald-Journal sneaked back into the
group's performance in Syracuse Thursday night and took photos after
a two-song time limit. So the photographers were banned from
Friday's concert, and Stones aide Neil Friedman said they wouldn't
be allowed back unless the newspaper's managing editor met with him.
   Managing Editor Tim Atseff took the ban in stride.
   ``Wild horses couldn't keep us from doing our job, and neither
will the promoters,'' Asteff said. ``Don't they know you can't
always get what you want? Come on, Mick, what's the big deal? It's
only rock 'n' roll. And our readers like it, too.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ASBURY PARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Springsteen at 40 hasn't lost his
appeal for female fans, and the presents he received for his
birthday today included a rock 'n' roll G-string _ a guitar string
with a dangling leaf.
   ``I figured if it gave Bruce a chuckle, that's fun,'' said the
garment's creator, Patricia Russoniello of Tinton Falls. She won a
``Bruce Card'' contest sponsored by the Asbury Park Press.
   Runner-up was 14-year-old Kerrie Jackson of England, who sent a
card with ``please'' written inside 37,000 times.
   The paper promised to forward all 145 cards and gifts entered in
the contest to Springsteen through his agent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, a frequent
target of radio talk show hosts, took to the airwaves with a live
call-in show of his own.
   Broadcasting Friday from the Big E, a state fair in western
Massachusetts, the one-time presidential candidate fielded questions
about his unpopular budget cuts and a variety of social issues.
   ``You're on the air, this is Gov. Mike Dukakis,'' the Democrat
said in the first installment of a regular show on station WSPR-AM.
   In the off-the-wall category, one caller asked him to intercede
in the case of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche. When a caller
accused him of lying about plans for a state prison, the unflappable
governor responded, ``You're wrong sir. I'm sorry.''
   It wasn't his first broadcast experience. In the 1970s Dukakis
hosted a public television show called ``The Advocates'' that
featured roundtable discussions of controversial issues.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Roots'' author Alex Haley is working
on another book, and it may include a story about losing a childhood
friendship with a white boy who said Haley would one day have to
call him ``Mister.''
   The Pulitzer-Prize winning author told students and faculty at
Lincoln University Friday about his boyhood friend Kermit.
   Haley said he remembers spending time with Kermit climbing a
persimmon tree in Henning, Tenn., and talking about the future.
   Haley said he pulled away from the friendship when the two boys
were about 10 because Kermit told Haley, ``Pretty soon you'll have
to start calling me `Mister.'''
   Both boys knew the statement was true in the 1930s, Haley said,
but it made him so uncomfortable that in a month the friendship was
over.
   Haley said he hopes to find Kermit someday and renew the
friendship.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Hoffa's daughter says she doubts a
magazine article describing the alleged murder and dismemberment of
her long-missing father is true because the FBI has never given the
family such information.
   ``It's terribly gory. It's terribly upsetting to the entire
family,'' Barbara Ann Crancer said this week after reading an
advance of the article in Playboy. ``It's a shame we had to read it
in a Playboy-type magazine.''
   A federally protected witness, Donald ``Tony the Greek'' Frankos,
told Playboy that Hoffa, the former Teamster leader who disappeared
July 30, 1975, in suburban Detroit, was shot, dismembered and buried
in concrete at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J.
   Crancer said she assumed the FBI would have notified her family
if the agency had information such as that given to Playboy by
Frankos.
   Crancer, who is an administrative law judge for the Missouri
Division of Workers Compensation, has sued the Justice Department
for release of the FBI's file on her father. No trial date has been
set.
