<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Bicycles     09-23 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Bicycles,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bicycles Prove Useful in Battered City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many residents of this hurricane-ravaged
city mounted bicycles to check on their homes and friends, dodging
toppled trees, wind-sheared roofs, broken gas lights and other
debris.
   Hurricane Hugo's torrential rains and 135 mph winds caused an
estimated $1 billion in damages in historic Charleston. Mayor Joseph
P. Riley Jr. imposed a 7 p.m. curfew Friday to deter looting, and
1,400 National Guardsmen joined police in patrolling the streets
early today.
   Among those pushing pedals were Dr. Bob Sadler, his wife and two
daughters. Their golden retriever, ``Snickers,'' maneuvered around
the debris on foot.
   ``We didn't know which streets would be under water,'' said
Sadler.
   The Sadlers spent Thursday night in Summerville, about 25 miles
inland, when it became clear Charleston would get the brunt of Hugo.
   The family returned to the battered city Friday morning to check
on damage, finding streets littered with planks, window frames,
shards of glass and other debris. Many of the city's historic homes
were damaged and its big oak trees topped by the force of the storm.
   ``I couldn't imagine it being as bad as they were saying,'' said
Sadler's wife, Francie. ``I didn't want to believe it. I cried when
I came back into town.''
   Attorney Tom S. Tisdale said he decided to use his 10-speed
bicycle because his car was low on gasoline and because some streets
were impassable in cars.
   ``Given the problems with the streets, it's easier and faster in
many cases to get around on bicycles,'' he said.
   In the luggage rack of his bicycle, Tisdale carried a folded blue
tarp that had covered his desk during the storm. Tisdale said his
office was not damaged, but a friend's roof was gone. Tisdale
planned to give the tarp to his friend to cover the gaping hole.
   Another bicyclist, Beth Hutton, stopped for a break at a street
corner across the street from City Hall, whose metal roof was blown
off.
   ``It's the only way to get around,'' she said. ``I came out to
look at family homes. One's water damaged. One's roof is damaged.
One's OK, except we'd like to take a bath.''
   Ms. Hutton said she didn't think Hugo would cause such extensive
damage.
   ``Lots of trees are down,'' she said.
   Katie Crouch peddled along Meeting Street, past damaged motels
and shops, to check the homes of friends who had evacuated.
   ``Everything is in shock right now,'' said Ms. Crouch, a high
school junior.
</TEXT>
