<FIRST>r i PM-IRA-Glance     09-23 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IRA-Glance,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look at Attacks Claimed by the IRA</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the major IRA attacks of recent
years on targets in Britain and continental Europe:
   July 20, 1982: A bomb exploded under the British army's bandstand
in Regent's Park, London, killing seven band members and injuring
28. On the same day, another bomb in the capital's Hyde Park killed
four soldiers.
   Dec. 17, 1983: A car bomb exploded outside Harrod's department
store on a London street packed with Christmas shoppers. Six people
were killed and 90 injured.
   Oct. 12, 1984: Five people were killed and 24 injured when an IRA
bomb exploded at the hotel in the southern English seaside town of
Brighton, where Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was staying during
her Conservative Party's convention. Mrs. Thatcher, the IRA's
declared target, was unhurt.
   May 1, 1988: Three British airmen stationed in West Germany were
killed in Nieuwbergen, Holland. One was fatally shot and two died an
hour later when a bomb went off in a discotheque frequented by
British troops. It was one of a series of IRA attacks on British
military personnel in continental Europe during the year.
   Aug. 1, 1988: A bomb in the dormitory at Inglis Barracks in
London killed one soldier and injured nine.
   Sept. 7, 1989: The wife of a British soldier, Heidi Hazell, 25,
was shot and killed near her home outside Dortmund, West Germany.
   Sept. 22, 1989: An explosion at the Royal Marines School of Music
in Deal killed 10 people and injured 22.
</TEXT>
