<FIRST>r a PM-`Strangler'Weds     09-23 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-`Strangler' Weds,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant in `Hillside Strangler' Case Weds in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALLA WALLA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Hillside Strangler'' inmate Kenneth
Bianchi has married a woman he met through the mail.
   Bianchi, 38, and his pen pal, Shirlee J. Book, 36, of Monterey,
La., were married in a 30-minute ceremony in the Washington State
Penitentiary chapel, prison spokesman Richard Bauer said Friday.
   The couple have corresponded by mail and telephone since 1986 but
didn't meet face to face until Wednesday, the day before the
wedding, Bauer said. A marriage license was issued Monday by the
Walla Walla County Auditor's Office.
   Bianchi is serving two life sentences for the slayings of two
Washington women in January 1979.
   He pleaded guilty to first-degree murder in five of the 10
``Hillside Strangler'' slayings in California, in which young women
were raped and strangled and their bodies dumped on hillsides around
Los Angeles in 1977 and 1978. His cousin, Angelo Buono Jr., is
imprisoned in California for nine of the killings.
   The newlyweds won't get a conjugal visit for two to three months,
Bauer said. Then they'll get to spend time together in a trailer on
the prison grounds.
   Bianchi and his bride each were allowed one attendant, but
neither the attendants' names nor the minister's will be released,
Bauer said.
   The spokesman didn't know if Book would move to Walla Walla.
</TEXT>
