<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0409 09-23 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0409,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug War Negotiations Fizzle Out in Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Republicans were, to CORRECT billion to million;
picks up 5th graf, The parties; Note, PM-Congress-Drugs should have carried
a bjt designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's war on drugs is caught in a
partisan battle in the Senate, with Democrats trying to add
prevention and treatment money and Republicans arguing the revision
would weaken the defense budget.
   ``If we're not willing to spend $150 million more, this is no
war,'' Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, said Friday after a week of
closed-door efforts to reach a compromise failed.
   The talks broke off Friday and no new negotiations were scheduled.
   Republicans were proposing to add $850 million to the $7.9
billion program Bush announced two weeks ago and Democrats were
holding out for an additional $1 billion, with no further talks
scheduled.
   The parties also were at odds over how to distribute cuts in
programs for money to go to the anti-drug effort.
   The breakdown threatened to create a logjam of money bills in the
Senate just before the Oct. 1 start of the fiscal year when the
funds ordinarily would be needed. Lawmakers said they might pass a
stopgap measure to keep federal workers on the job and benefit
checks flowing.
   The chief Republican negotiator, Sen. Mark O. Hatfield, R-Ore.,
said the two sides were actually fairly close and said he hoped the
parties would take ``a clear-eyed, Monday morning view'' and resume
bargaining.
   ``We have to wage this war and the sooner we get at it the better
it's going to be,'' Hatfield said.
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the chief Democratic negotiator,
said the White House had been ``a shadow participant'' in the
negotiations and that its reluctance to compromise was the key
problem.
   ``There comes a time when you have to fish or cut bait,'' said
Byrd, the chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
   Republican lawmakers said they were frequently on the phone to
White House chief of staff John Sununu on Thursday when a marathon
bargaining session ended at midnight.
   Sununu was in the office of Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas Friday morning for a strategy session with GOP senators,
national drug policy director William Bennett and budget director
Richard Darman.
   Of the $1 billion Democrats would add, $800 million would be
aimed at stemming demand for drugs through education and prevention
programs and through treatment. The rest would go to local law
enforcement.
   Democrats would finance their program with an across-the-board
cut of 0.3 percent in federal spending plus selected cuts to be
determined by congressional subcommittees.
   Republicans were offering to add $850 million to the program,
including $750 million for the so-called demand side programs of
treatment and prevention and the rest for local law enforcement.
   They would get additional money through a 0.4 percent
across-the-board cut in spending, Hatfield said. But Republicans
were holding out for additional flexibility to protect defense
procurement from the full brunt of across-the-board cuts.
   Since the bargaining began, Democrats cut their proposed increase
by more than half to compromise with Republicans. GOP senators said
Byrd's initial plan, with its across-the-board reduction of more
than 0.5 percent, would have been too hard on defense.
   And inclusion of selected cuts also represented a partial
concession to Republican demands.
   Byrd told a news conference that Republicans asked for
concessions ``and we said, OK, we'll do that, but lets beef up that
treatment side, that prevention side.'' He and other Democratic
lawmakers dismissed the notion that their proposal would weaken
defense.
   ``The administration was unwilling to let a $300 billion defense
budget bear a less than one-half of one percent cut to beef up the
war on drugs,'' Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., told reporters.
</TEXT>
