<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Martinez-Abortion     09-23 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Martinez-Abortion,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Orders Clinic Closed, Seeks New Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez is seeking emergency
rules to protect women at private abortion clinics in Florida after
ordering a Miami clinic closed because of reports of botched
abortions.
   ``This is a pure pro-health issue,'' Martinez said at a Friday
news conference. ``This is for the health of individuals
irregardless of philosophy on the substance of the abortion issue.''
   Martinez told Health and Rehabilitative Services Secretary Greg
Coler to ``take all steps necessary to remove the license of this
clinic.''
   The action comes after reports of improper abortions by
unlicensed physicians resulting in ruptured uteri and hysterectomies
at the Dadeland Medical Center, now doing business as the Women's
Service Center.
   ``There is no legal reason, no health reason, for this order,''
responded Susan Hoffman, director of the center. ``We've done
nothing against the law. We've helped thousands of women. I see this
as totally ludicrous.''
   Peter Dunbar, the governor's general counsel, said any emergency
regulations drawn up by HRS for abortion clinics would be in effect
for 90 days. After that, the new rules would be subject to public
hearings and HRS board approval to become permanent.
   By that time, the Legislature will have decided whether to go
along with Martinez's proposals to further restrict access to
abortions. The session is scheduled for Oct. 10-13.
   Martinez has denied he was trying to bypass the Legislature by
using the Miami situation to enact emergency regulations.
   Yet in his letter to Coler, the governor said conditions at the
Miami clinic ``are precisely why I have called for increased
regulation of abortion clinics to protect the health of women.''
   The new rules, Martinez said, will not be as strict as his
proposal for the special session to make private abortion clinics
adhere to the same standards as ambulatory care clinics.
   Martinez said HRS should not be blamed for the problems at the
Miami clinic, saying the agency doesn't have the power at present to
uncover them. He said he doesn't know whether abortion clinics
throughout the state have similar practices.
   Brian Ballard, the governor's chief of operations, said
veterinary clinics have more stringent regulations than abortion
centers.
   Neither Martinez nor Dunbar would be specific about the kinds of
regulations being sought, but both said they would be designed to
protect the health of women seeking abortions _ not to restrict
their access to an abortion.
</TEXT>
