<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Pope-Gorbachev     09-23 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Pope-Gorbachev,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Official Discusses Possible Pope-Gorbachev Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican has confirmed that a Roman
Catholic Church official met with the Soviet ambassador to Italy to
discuss a possible meeting between Pope John Paul II and President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Such a meeting would be the first between the leader of the
world's 850 million Roman Catholics and the head of the officially
atheist Soviet Union.
   Joaquin Navarro, the Vatican spokesman, Friday confirmed a
newspaper report that Archbishop Angelo Sodano of the Vatican's
Secretariat of State had gone to the Soviet Embassy in Rome about 10
days earlier to meet Ambassador Nikolai Lunkov.
   The spokesman told reporters the meeting involved ``preparation
for a possible visit by President Gorbachev to the Vatican.''
   Navarro gave no dates for such a meeting. Gorbachev is expected
to visit Italy sometime in November, however.
   The spokesman did not comment on another part of the report in
the Rome daily La Repubblica that said Sodano told Lunkov the
Vatican was ready to consider establishing diplomatic relations with
the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
