<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Norway-Extremist     09-23 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Norway-Extremist,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Immigration Leader Convicted For Bomb Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARENDAL, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A founder of an anti-immigration group was
convicted of plotting to bomb a refugee center and sentenced to one
year in prison, news reports said.
   Arne Myrdal, 53, called his conviction on Friday ``absurd'' and
``a political judgment,'' according to the Norwegian news agency
NTB. He was expected to appeal.
   The Agder Country Court said evidence, including dynamite and a
hand-drawn map of a new refugee reception center near this southern
Norway town, proved that Myrdal intended to bomb the center, NTB
reported.
   Myrdal helped found the People's Movement Against Immigration in
October 1987, after the annual number of asylum seekers in Norway
increased tenfold in two years to about 8,600 people.
   A second defendant in the case, Fred Skauen, 34, was convicted of
conspiracy and threatening to kill a police informer who acted as a
prosecution witness, the news report said. He was sentenced to eight
months in prison, according to the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
