<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--China-Waste     09-23 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--China-Waste,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Officials Seize New Luxury Office Building From Ministry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Waste watchers in the Chinese government have
seized a new luxury office building from a ministry accused of
ignoring state orders to avoid extravagance, according to an
official report today.
   The China Daily newspaper quoted He Yong, vice minister of
supervision, as saying, ``This violates the state's regulations on
construction standards for executive office buildings as well as the
present austerity drive.''
   The central government has demanded for the past year that all
public offices sharply reduce spending as part of a policy to
counter inflation, rising budget deficits and excessive economic
growth.
   The six-story building on Beijing's main Changan Avenue contains
marble walls and floors, central air conditioning and other luxuries
for top officials. It cost $31 million, 3{ times the amount planned.
   He Yong said the building, completed last year, will be turned
over to the Bureau of Government Offices Administration.
</TEXT>
