<DOCNO> AP890923-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ZsaZsaTrial     09-23 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>A `Zsa Zsa G'Bear' Comes Between Actress and Key Witness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense witness admitted she
received a teddy bear from Zsa Zsa Gabor before testifying that she
saw a motorcycle policeman drag the actress from a car and kick her.
   Miss Gabor explained she handed Rosa Perick a ``Zsa Zsa G'Bear,''
replete with satin nightgown, as a gift for Ms. Perick's son.
   Ms. Perick was the first witness in the cop-slapping trial to
corroborate Miss Gabor's story about her arrest. She said Miss Gabor
made other offers during her two visits to the actress' house this
week.
   Miss Gabor ``offered me whatever I wanted,'' Ms. Perick said.
   Miss Gabor faces a possible 18-month jail sentence if convicted
of misdemeanor battery on a police officer, disobeying an officer's
orders, driving with an expired license and having an open container
of alcohol in her car.
   Miss Gabor does not deny slapping Officer Paul Kramer. But she
insists she lashed out in self-defense after he cursed her and
dragged her from her Rolls-Royce on June 14 when he spotted expired
registration tags on the car.
   Deputy District Attorney Elden Fox cited Ms. Perick's remarks to
imply that she stood to benefit by buttressing Miss Gabor's case.
   Elden asked Ms. Perick how she supported herself.
   ``When I work, I have income. When I don't work, I don't have
income,'' she responded. Under further questioning, she began to
explain that she had taken a mortgage on her home when Miss Gabor
broke in: ``I will help you.''
   ``I'm sure you will,'' Fox quipped to snickers from the packed
Beverly Hills courthouse.
   Fox asked Perick why defense attorney William Graysen invited her
to Miss Gabor's house on Tuesday, the day Miss Gabor took the
witness stand.
   ``I guess to review the case,'' Ms. Perick replied. ``We had
nothing else to speak (of),'' she said.
   Graysen said he planned to call up to four more witnesses for the
defense before wrapping up his case. But he conceded Miss Gabor
likely would be convicted of driving without a valid license, a
misdemeanor.
</TEXT>
