<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Hugo-FollyBeach Bjt   09-23 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Folly Beach, Bjt,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barrier Islands off South Carolina Devastated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FOLLY BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo's six-hour blast left
Folly Beach unrecognizable even to its mayor. Up the coast, the
storm's wake left two other barrier islands cut off, and sliced
another in two.
   Folly Beach, the town and island just south of Charleston,
virtually lost its entire beachfront row of homes.
   ``I don't know where we are,'' Mayor Bob Linville said during a
tour of the area. ``All of my usual landmarks are gone.''
   One missing dwelling was the Atlantic House Restaurant, which had
survived years of serious erosion that left it literally sitting
atop pilings in the ocean, approachable only by foot bridge. After
Hugo, all that remained was its red shingle roof.
   ``About 30 percent of the houses on the island are no longer
habitable, if they're even here,'' said Claude Wade of the Folly
Beach Police Department.
   Linville estimated the damage at tens of millions of dollars and
said hundreds of buildings had been damaged or destroyed.
   Most of the seaward houses in the town of 2,000 residents either
were cracked open or without roofs or windows.
   Along the ocean, support poles for beach houses had nothing to
support, their houses having been washed away by Hugo's 12- to
17-foot tidal surge. Arctic Avenue, about 50 feet from the ocean,
looked like a dirt road, covered with sand and the debris of smashed
beach houses.
   The storm showed that the destruction was often a game of chance.
One house was knocked off its foundation and with a wall missing.
But a china cabinet remained standing as did two plates inside.
   Demolished houses spewed mattresses, clothes, and furniture along
the beach.
   The Holiday Inn, which sits on a slab of concrete 50 feet from
the ocean, seemed to weather the storm remarkably well despite its
proximity to the ocean. Its upper floors remained intact even though
the first floor was demolished. Farther up the coast, two barrier
islands _ Sullivan's Island and the Isle of Palms _ were cut off
from land because the storm knocked out its only link _ the
swing-span Ben Sawyer Bridge.
   On the Isle of Palms, which hosts the U.S. Clay Court Tennis
Championships, the hurricane ripped the fishing pier out of the
water and destroyed million-dollar waterfront homes.
   About 100 boats that had been docked at the Wild Dunes Marina
were ``stacked up like cordwood'' across the marina on Goat Island,
said Ben Moise, a state Wildlife and Marine Resources Department
official.
   Hugo created a 100- to 200-foot-wide channel of water through
Pawleys Island, midway between Charleston and Myrtle Beach,
according to Jack Sellers, a pilot from Columbia who flew people to
the coast to check their property.
   ``There are now two Pawleys Islands, if you will,'' Sellers said.
   Back on Folly Beach, Dean DuBani walked along the streets Friday
afternoon carrying a small satchel and looking for a ride.
   While many other heeded evacaution orders before the storm,
DuBani said he remained and partied with some other people in an
ocean front house as Hugo smashed ashore.
   ``It was incredible,'' he said. ``Everything was just floating
by.''
   DuBani said he left the house when it began breaking up, and
walked across the street to a neighbor's house whose door had been
blown open.
   ``I got scared and just grabbed my clothes. This is all I have
left,'' he said, pointing to his pouch that contained a fishing
pole, a can of beer, some swimming fins, a snorkel, several shirts
and a few pairs of pants.
   ``Thinking about heading to Key West,'' he said before hitching a
ride out of town with a blonde woman in a sports car.
   But Bud Tetric was determined to stay.
   ``Going to rebuild,'' he said of his demolished house. ``I pay
taxes, and, if I pay taxes, I should have full use of my property.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
