<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0433 09-23 0954</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,0989</SECOND>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to clarify implications of a lack of local
government, ADD distance between Phnom Penh and Pursat, Battambang, and
RECAST 14th graf to clarify role of drought, guerrillas; pickup 15th graf
pvs, `We buy...' ^By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURSAT, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ravaged by two decades of war and bloody
revolution, Cambodia now faces a drought that is expected to cut
rice and fish cultivation by 25 percent and threaten many with
starvation.
   A lack of local government to provide social services or
otherwise help people makes the prospects for this nation of 8
million appear even bleaker.
   ``If the war won't kill you then you might die because of no
water,'' said Treang Suon, a 37-year-old mother of four from Veal
village in the Pursat province, 90 miles northwest of Phnom Penh.
``And there is no government to help us along.''
   Interviews with peasants, government officials, teachers and
Western aid officials in the provinces of Pursat and Kampong Chhnang
gave a dark picture of the future for Cambodia.
   The country appears poised to slide into a new phase of civil
conflict now that the Vietnamese, this nation's occupiers for the
last decade, say they will withdraw the last of their troops by
Tuesday.
   Fighting between Cambodian government troops and guerrillas from
the Khmer Rouge resistance group already is intensifying in
Battambang, 140 miles northwest of Pursat. A Western doctor in
Pursat said his hospital has seen a twofold increase in gunshot
wounds over the past two months.
   ``Now we average about five a day,'' he said. ``The Khmer Rouge
are moving about very freely and the peasants are scared.''
   The economy, too, is in deep trouble.
   Fish cultivation and timber production have fallen in Pursat for
two straight years. Due to the late and light rains this year,
production of rice, the staple crop for the whole country, also is
sure to fall.
   Three decades of peace ended in Cambodia in 1970 when a military
coup ousted Prince Norodom Sihanouk, dragging Cambodia into the
Vietnam War. The Khmer Rouge took power in 1975 and killed hundreds
of thousands of people under their radical brand of agrarian
communism.
   Vietnam invaded the country in December 1978 and installed a
pro-Hanoi regime in Phnom Penh. A resistance coalition led by
Sihanouk has been battling the Vietnamese and Cambodian government
troops.
   If the economy worsens, the government will lose legitimacy,
making its battle against the resistance front that much harder.
   The biggest loser will be Cambodia's people.
   Time was when the Moslem people of Ro Leap village took the
half-day walk over palm-lined paths and verdant paddies to Lake
Tonle Sap to fish the once-bountiful waters. But now there is a
drought, and bands of Khmer Rouge guerrillas would make a trip too
risky.
   ``We buy our fish now and only eat it on special occasions,''
said Ty Chouk, a 37-year-old farmer. ``We used to fish everyday.''
   The catch in Pursat province fell 41 percent between 1987 and
1988 to 4,120 metric tons, according to Khang Heang, vice chief of
the provincial committee. Another drop in 1989 is expected,
government officials said.
   They still fish in nearby Veal village, but the residents no
longer wander into the forest near Ro Leap to cut hardwood timber
and bamboo for their homes.
   Landmines laid by the government and the Khmer Rouge have blown
up too many people.
   ``The folks near the lake don't come up here anymore,'' Ty Chouk
said. ``Only we know where the government mines are because we laid
them in the ground. Other villages are too scared to risk their
lives. Even we don't go into the high areas anymore. That belongs to
the Pol Pot people and their mines.''
   Timber cultivation also fell in Pursat between 1987 and 1988,
dropping 16 percent to 5,000 cubic meters, Khang Heang said.
   Bad weather has been another problem. Scarce rain pushed rice
planting back from May until August, raising doubts as to whether
the peasants around Pursat would be able to plant a second crop of
rice.
   ``My family will go hungry this year,'' said Mrs. Suon, spitting
a red wad of beetlenut juice in the dirt. ``We can't live only on
coconuts and onions, we must have rice.''
   Another blow to agriculture has been the government's policy to
forcibly conscript many young men.
   San Poen, a 43-year-old father of four, had his two sons taken
away by the military.
   ``They were rounded up after a movie show,'' he said. ``It is
good that they are serving the country but I need them, too, to farm
the fields. I had to drop some land this year and am farming less.
So we will have too little to eat.''
   Khang Heang estimated that rice cultivation in Pursat would fall
between 12 percent and 25 percent.
   ``If the weather doesn't get better the people could starve,'' he
said.
   A Ministry of Finance official said he believed nationwide
production would probably fall 25 percent.
   Yet another problem is the lack of local administration to help
people deal with the crisis.
   At Veal village, which is responsible for eight communes holding
about 1,500 people, the local government office consists of a
ramshackle two-story house. Three rooms open onto a courtyard shaded
by coconut trees. Freshly painted signs, ``Justice,''
``Administration'' and ``Economy'' hang from the rooms.
   ``These are our departments,'' says Hem Pheach, a Communist Party
official. The rooms contain no chairs or tables. There is no paper,
no phone. In one room, a chicken clucks in a corner, searching for
food.
   ``We lack some materials,'' Hem says quietly, ``then maybe we can
get on with our job.''
</TEXT>
