<FIRST>u i PM-Hugo-Caribbean     09-23 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Caribbean,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Remain Homeless; Officials Complain Aid Slow In Coming</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Caribbean
residents remained at the mercy of the elements nearly a week after
Hurricane Hugo destroyed their homes and communities.
   Officials in the Virgin Islands and in Puerto Rico complained
Friday that while Washington readily flew in troops to stop the
looting and restore order, disaster relief was slow in coming.
   Tens of thousands of people remained in shelters or were roughing
it wherever they could.
   ``I think the governor was wrong in telling the people the
military was coming without telling them (when) food was coming,
water was coming,'' said territorial Sen. Lilliana Belardo de O'Neal.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan and a group of congressmen were
to begin a two-day fact-finding trip to Puerto Rico and the Virgin
Islands today. A congressional aide said the lawmakers planned to
bring 20 cases of baby formula, 30 chain saws and 2,100 transistor
radios.
   The congressmen, led by Rep. George Miller, D.-Calif., also will
consider special aid requests by local officials.
   The U.S. Justice Department obtained authority Friday from Virgin
Islands Gov. Alexander Farrelly to order FBI agents and deputy U.S.
marshals to enforce all laws on the islands and to prosecute any
looters, officials said.
   Officials say at least 27 people died when Hugo steamrolled
through Guadeloupe, Montserrat, Antigua, the British and U.S. Virgin
Islands and Puerto Rico on Sunday before hitting the Carolinas on
Thursday, where it left 11 dead. Losses were estimated in the
billions of dollars.
   President Bush on Wednesday declared the Virgin Islands a
disaster area and ordered 1,200 troops, mostly military police, to
St. Croix in part to stop widespread looting.
   There were no reports of looting Friday, but virtually every
store in Christiansted, the capital of St. Croix, appeared to have
been cleaned out.
   The National Guard has acknowledged that some of its members took
part in the looting, and several witnesses said some police also
were involved.
   Lt. Gov. Derek Hodge of the Virgin Islands said Friday that Hugo
left homeless more than 45,000 people _ about 90 percent of St.
Croix's population. St. Croix, about 70 miles east of Puerto Rico,
is the main island in the group that includes St. Thomas and St.
John.
   Hodge said damage was tentatively estimated at $4 billion.
   ``The island is almost a total disaster,'' he said in a radio
broadcast.
   He appealed to the National Guard, the police and other public
employees to return to work in full force despite the continued
chaos on the island. He said the National Guard was operating at 40
percent strength and the police at 80 percent.
   Ms. Belardo de O'Neal said she and four other senators met with
Gov. Alexander Farrelly on Friday to find out when people can expect
relief supplies.
   The St. Croix Red Cross vice chairman, Evelyn Crittenden,
complained that the army failed to promptly fly in food, clothes,
bedding and medicine.
   ``Here we are, and this is what I have,'' she said, pointing to
some old clothes piled on a table and the floor of an office.
   Hodge said federal disaster specialists arrived on St. Croix
Tuesday but were unable to request immediate help because of
communications problems. He said the Virgin Islands needs
``everything from wrenches to chain saws to medical supplies.''
   In Puerto Rico, 70 percent of the island's 3.3. million residents
remained without running water and 20,000 were still housed in
shelters. Large parts of San Juan, the capital, and several towns in
the northeast also remained without power, officials said.
   Hundreds of residents in San Juan stood in long lines waiting for
water, ice and gasoline.
   When Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon arrived in the northern coastal
town of Canovanas on Friday to inspect local shelters, angry
residents complained they had received no govenment aid since the
storm.
   ``We're all in the street. We don't have any food, water or
light. Our houses blew away,'' resident Gladys Cruz told the
governor.
   In the British colony of Montserrat, Gov. Christopher Turner said
30 percent of the homes will have to be rebuilt and another 30
percent will need extensive repairs. He said about 3,000 of the
island's 12,500 residents were left homeless.
   While the 39-square-mile island still lacked power, some water
and phone service was being restored, he said.
</TEXT>
