<HEAD>Deaths Caused by Hurricane Hugo in Caribbean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   According to latest figures available, 27 to 29 people died when
Hurricane Hugo plowed across the islands of the northeast Caribbean
earlier this week, razing homes, cutting power and communications
and leaving thousands without fresh water.
   Six others died Wednesday when a French rescue helicopter crashed
off Guadeloupe.
   Here's an island-by-island look at the deaths in the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PUERTO RICO _ Six people were killed, including four by drowning
and electrocution, according to police.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   U.S. VIRGIN ISLANDS _ Lt. Gov. Derek Hodge said four people were
killed on St. Croix. However, Evelyn Crittenden, vice chairman of
the island's Red Cross, put the number at six. There has been no
information yet of any deaths on St. Thomas and St. John.
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MONTSERRAT _ Ten died on this British island, according to
Governor-General Christopher Turner.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GUADELOUPE _ Five were killed during the hurricane in this French
overseas department, according to French government officials on the
sister island of Martinique. Six more died in the crash of a French
rescue helicopter, according to the French Defense Ministry in Paris.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ANTIGUA _ Two were killed in this former British colony,
according to officials.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ST. KITTS and NEVIS _ It is unknown whether there were deaths or
injuries because communications to this island federation remain
knocked out.
</TEXT>
