<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 0538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseStudents     09-23 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Students,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students Argue For Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Chinese students seeking asylum
testified that a return to their homeland would mean a life as bleak
as their families endured during China's Cultural Revolution.
   The students, who fled to San Francisco after leading an
anti-government protest in Tokyo following the June crackdown in
Beijing, were emotional Friday during the first day of their hearing.
   Asked through a Cantonese translator if she would be willing to
return to China, Hoy Yu Li replied, ``I would rather die.''
   The 27-year-old linguistics student testified about her father's
imprisonment during the Cultural Revolution and her own fears that
her political activity while studying in Japan would lead her to the
same fate.
   ``If we return, it's like a death row. My life will be like my
father's and many others','' she said.
   Her fiance, Luo Jian Guang, said when his father died last July,
he was afraid to return for the funeral.
   ``I would never return to China because if I return to China,
they know my name, they will imprison me,'' he said.
   The students were led handcuffed into the court, but federal
Immigration Judge Bernard Hornbach ordered the handcuffs removed.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service attorney Beverly Phillips
said the INS had no particular position on the matter but filed a
brief containing a State Department recommendation that asylum not
be granted because the students hadn't proved they face persecution
if they return to China.
   Hoy and Luo helped organize and publicize a rally in Toyko on
June 4, just after Red Army troops began their assault on student
protesters in Beijing. They also signed a petition protesting the
action.
   Immediately afterward they began receiving threatening phone
calls warning them that their demonstration, photographed by Chinese
embassy officials, could lead them into trouble. Both testified
Friday that they believed the calls came from Chinese authorities.
   They fled through Hong Kong and have been seeking political
asylum since arriving in San Francisco in August. Their attorney,
Eugene Wong, said there has been only one other case in which a
Chinese person came into the United States after the crackdown to
seek asylum.
   Wong said the case could set a precedent for other Chinese
residents in the United States who have spoken out against the
current regime in Beijing.
   The U.S. government estimates there are 73,000 Chinese students
in the country. President Bush decided in June to allow students who
were in the country at the time of the Beijing crackdown to remain
here.
   Hornbach continued the hearing until Sept. 29 and advised Wong to
seek Hoy's release from custody so she could seek medical treatment
for ulcer-like symptoms.
   David Ilchert, regional INS director, said Hoy would be examined
by a doctor today. She was being held at a Santa Clara County
women's detention facility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
