<FIRST>r i PM-MotherTeresa     09-23 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mother Teresa,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chest Pains Subsided But Condition Still Serious, Doctor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa was still in
serious condition although the fever and the chest pains she
suffered for more than two weeks had subsided, her doctor said today.
   ``But her condition is not critical,'' said Dr. Rajen Wats at the
Woodlands Nursing Home, the hospital where the 79-year-old Roman
Catholic nun was admitted Sept. 5 with a high fever and irregular
heartbeat.
   Mother Teresa's condition twice become critical after she
suffered a heart attack in the hospital's intensive care unit Sept.
8 and occasional chest pains since then.
   ``We will have to observe her for two more weeks before we can
say if she is out of danger or not,'' Wats said.
   Doctors have said that after she leaves the hospital, Mother
Teresa will have to give up the hectic schedule that is partly
blamed for her illness.
   Despite poor health in recent years, she has traveled widely to
help the destitute and the dying, work that earned her a Nobel Peace
Prize in 1979.
