<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   09-23 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0479,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Use Barbed Wire to Stop Women's March; White Supremacists
Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 200 arrested, including white supremacist,
Winnie Mandela ordered to leave Pretoria, ABC reporter detained. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police blocked entrances to the
capital today and strung barbed wire down a main street to stop an
unauthorized march by anti-apartheid women's groups. Organizers said
about 200 people were arrested.
   Police also used batons to clear black bystanders from Pretoria's
central square after scuffles broke out when right-wing whites in
swastika-marked khaki uniforms began hustling blacks away from the
site of an approved pro-apartheid rally. One white right-winger and
several blacks were arrested.
   The white extremists had received permission for their rally, but
the women's planned march to government headquarters was banned
because organizers refused to apply for a permit. The church where
marchers were to meet was blocked off with rolls of barbed wire and
guarded by scores of police officers.
   Zeni Tshongweni, a spokeswoman for the march organizers, said
about 200 people were arrested when they tried to assemble near the
Union Buildings, the government headquarters which was the intended
destination of the march. She said several people were injured when
police used whips and dogs to disperse the crowd.
   Police detained Richard Sergay, correspondent for the American
television network ABC, and several other journalists.
   Two buses, carrying Winnie Mandela, wife of imprisoned African
National Congress leader Nelson Mandela, and other blacks were
chased through the streets by about 25 yellow police vehicles with
sirens screaming and lights flashing. The police stopped the buses
and ordered Mrs. Mandela and the other occupants to leave Pretoria.
   ``We came here peacefully but they are seeking violence,'' Mrs.
Mandela told CBS News.
   ``It is the same as any other country in the world. People can't
break the law,'' said Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, standing
among riot police behind the barbed wire that blocked the entrance
to St. Alban's Anglican Cathedral.
   A two-page notice was tacked to the door of the church, saying
the government obtained a court order to stop a church service and
the planned march to the Union Buildings.
   Two tear gas cannon trucks were parked nearby and hundreds of
police lined the streets as the city center came to a standstill.
   The government banned the march because the organizers refused to
ask for official permission, although women's groups said they had
notified top government officials including President F.W. de Klerk
and talked with Pretoria traffic police.
   The government granted permission for two white supremacist
groups to hold rallies two blocks from the cathedral because they
had sought permission, officials said.
   At the first rally a banner called for the hanging of Nelson
Mandela and for the release from prison of Barend Strydom, a white
former policeman convicted early this year of killing seven black
people in a shooting spree in the center of Pretoria.
   As the meeting ended, an altercation began when about 40 blacks
tried to walk across the square where the rally was held and were
stopped by members of the Afrikaner Resistance Movement, who wear
khaki uniforms and use swastika symbols.
   Police began herding away the blacks, who were flashing peace
signs, and calling out to the whites, ``Peace, we all have the same
blood.'' Suddenly police began running through the square, arresting
blacks, letting their dogs loose and ordering reporters and everyone
else from the area.
   It was not immediately clear whether the second right-wing rally
would be allowed to go ahead.
   Organizers of the women's march said police blocked almost all
traffic from the black townships around Pretoria.
   Traffic was backed up from Pretoria's main thoroughfare to the
freeway leading north from Johannesburg as police at roadblocks
stopped and searched buses and cars filled with women and turned
them away.
   About 30,000 women had been expected to defy the ban and try to
march.
   About 200 women, most of them white, made their way to a park at
the bottom of the ridge where the Union Buildings stand, but police
arrived and ordered them to leave. They did not move quickly enough
and several were arrested.
   A.R. Dawood of the Transvaal Indian Congress said police hit some
of the women with their batons.
   In obtaining a court order against the women's march, lawyers for
the police had argued that the proximity of the right-wing rallies
might lead to conflict.
   The women's groups said they had made extensive arrangements,
including training parade marshals and setting up first-aid
stations, to ensure their march was peaceful.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate neighborhoods, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
