<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-ETA     09-23 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-ETA,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>ETA Claims Parcel Bombing That Killed Fish Store Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILBAO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Basque separatist group ETA claimed
responsibility today for the parcel bombing death of the owner of a
fish store in this northern city and said it had mistaken the man
for a policeman.
   In a statement published in the radical Basque newspaper Egin,
ETA said the killing Sept. 12 was ``an irreparable error and
mistake'' and apologized to the victim's family.
   ETA claimed the bomb was intended for a policeman who used the
name of the dead man as a cover, but added: ``The sole
responsibility is ours for this death.''
   Luis Reina Mesonera died of injuries suffered when a parcel he
received in the mail exploded as he tried to open it, police said.
   ETA seeks independence from Spain for the three-province northern
Basque region. In its 21-year campaign of violence, ETA has claimed
responsibility for killing more than 600 people, including 13 so far
this year.
   ETA recently claimed responsibility for a parcel bomb that killed
a prison guard's mother Aug. 11 and for another parcel bomb sent to
a Basque businessman Sept. 5 that was detected and safely detonated.
   On Wednesday, a parcel bomb explosion killed a postman in the
Basque city of San Sebastian. No group claimed responsibility, but
Interior Minister Jose Luis Corcuera told SER radio today that ETA
was probably responsible.
   ETA is an acronym for Basque Land and Liberty in the Basque
language.
</TEXT>
