<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-RedStar     09-23 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Red Star,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO FIX CYCLE DESIGNATOR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Communist Red Star To Be Removed From Public Buildings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The red star, the symbol of Communist
rule in the Soviet bloc for four decades, will be removed from all
public buildings in Hungary to reflect the country's move to a
multiparty democracy.
   Government spokesman Zsolt Bajnok told reporters Friday the time
had come to replace the red star with the Hungarian coat of arms.
   ``In previous decades, the symbols of the working class movement
were widely used, but now state symbols will take their place on
public buildings,'' he said.
   Bajnok did not say exactly when the red star will be removed from
the top of Budapest's sprawling Parliament building. He said removal
of the huge symbol would be quite expensive, involving the use of
helicopters.
   Currently the red star decorates all Hungarian public buildings,
including government ministries, radio and television, regional and
local government buildings and factories.
</TEXT>
