<HEAD>White Man Arrested in Death of Zola Budd's Father</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Removes reference to suspect's race in lede. Pickup 2nd, `Police...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested a young
man in connection with the fatal shooting of Frank Budd, father of
track star Zola Budd, officers said today.
   Police said they found a shotgun and pickup truck which were
missing from Budd's farmhouse when they arrested the 24-year-old man
Friday night in Welkom, 60 miles north of the farm near Bloemfontein.
   Police did not identify the man, but the independent South
African Press Association said he was expected to appear in court
Monday on a charge of murder. Newspapers said today that police had
been seeking a young man who had been doing construction work on the
farm, where Budd's body was found Friday.
   Police said the 56-year-old retired printer had two shotgun
wounds in the left side of his body when it was found in the bedroom
of a house he built on the farm of a friend.
   Ms. Budd and her father did not communicate in recent years and
he did not attend his daughter's April 15 wedding in Bloemfontein,
saying he had not been invited. ``I don't know what to say. What can
a person say?'' Ms. Budd said upon learning of her father's death
Friday ngith.
   Budd was divorced from Ms. Budd's mother.
   Zola Budd rose to prominence as a frail, barefooted teen-ager who
broke a string of South African and world records.
   Many sports fans remember her collision with American runner Mary
Decker during the 3,000-meter run in the 1984 Olympics in Los
Angeles.
   Decker, the favorite, was knocked out of the race, while Budd
finished seventh to a chorus of boos.
   Ms. Budd set several distance running world records during her
career and twice won the world cross-country championship while
living and training in Britain. But she was constantly dogged by
anti-apartheid protesters who said she should not be allowed to
compete because of her South African connections.
   Ms. Budd, 23, returned to South Africa in May 1988 and, after
marryig South African businessman Mike Pieterse, said she would
remain in her homeland.
</TEXT>
