<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Prison     09-23 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Prison,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Visits Maximum Security Prison for Mafiosi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOLTERRA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today visited a maximum
security prison for Mafia criminals, blessing the inmates and urging
them to break free from their ``moral chains.''
   The pope, who is on a three-day tour of Tuscany, said he was a
``brother among brothers'' with the 150 convicts housed in the 15th
century fortress prison that sits atop this medieval hill town.
   Known as the Fortezza (fort), the prison was a castle begun by
Walter de Brienne, Duke of Athens, in 1343 and completed by Lorenzo
the Magnificent in 1472. It has been used as a prison since 1848.
   Prison officials said most of the inmates were convicted of
belonging to organized crime syndicates such as the Sicilian Mafia,
Neapolitan Camorra and Calabrian 'ndrangheta. Many were convicted of
murder, and 15 are serving life sentences.
   The inmates clapped and sang as the pope entered the prison
courtyard. The area, enclosed by iron bars, normally serves as space
for the inmates to play sports.
   Many prisoners bowed and kissed John Paul's ring as he walked
down the carpeted aisle and patted them on the head.
   ``Here I am among you, brother among brothers,'' the pope said,
``for a visit looked forward to not only by you, but also by me for
the affection that I bring you, to people who wish to reconcile
themselves with society and find a new place to collaborate
constructively for the common good.''
   ``There is a liberation of physical chains, which for human
beings certainly has great importance, as you can testify. But there
is also ... a liberation from moral chains.''
   The pope said he was praying that the inmates show ``perseverance
in your desire to collaborate in the construction of a free and just
society.''
   Before the pope spoke, a 26-year-old murder convict gave the pope
a welcoming speech.
   ``Your salute and your blessing are very important for making us
accept ourselves and making us accepted by the whole community,''
said Rocco Morano, serving a 21-year sentence for murder in
Calabria. ``This meeting is a turning point of redemption for all of
us.''
   It was the third time John Paul has visited an Italian prison. In
December 1983, he went to Rome's Rebibbia prison to forgive Mehmet
Ali Agca, the Turkish gunman who shot him in St. Peter's Square in
1981. The pope has also visited the prison in Civitavecchia near
Rome.
   The pope celebrated Mass in Voleterra's Piazza dei Priori,
bordered by medieval mansions, before heading for nearby Lucca. On
Sunday he will visit Pisa before returning to Rome.
</TEXT>
