<DOCNO> AP890923-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland     09-23 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Journalist Picked to Head State Media Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki today
named an opposition journalist and specialist in Soviet affairs to
head the committee that controls state media, the official news
agency announced.
   Andrzej Drawicz, 57, a Solidarity activist and former political
prisoner, will take over the chairmanship of the Radio and
Television Committee from the former longtime government spokesman
Jerzy Urban, the PAP agency said.
   The appointment is considered one of the most important for the
East bloc's first government not led by Communists, removing control
of the mass media from the Communist Party for the first time since
World War II.
   Mazowiecki has promised that the state-owned mass media will
become pluralistic and honest.
   ``The government wants to tell the truth and enable freedom of
speech for all sections of public opinion. The right of access to
radio and television must be equal to all,'' he said in unveiling
his government to parliament earlier this month.
   The Mazowiecki Cabinet, installed Sept. 12, includes four
Communists among its 24 members.
   The head of radio and television was the biggest remaining
question mark of Mazowiecki's government. The post will not retain
Cabinet status, reflecting the new government's view that there
should be nothing like an ``information minister'' shaping public
opinion.
   ``This change is not just a replacement at the post of chairman,
but it is an issue of credibility, and that is why it is so
significant for the new government,'' said Krzysztof Kozlowski, a
Solidarity senator from Krakow who negotiated mass media reforms
during ``round-table'' negotiations this year.
   Drawicz, a Warsaw native, has no significant experience in
broadcasting, but he is respected as a journalist and known for his
admiration of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policies of
perestroika and glasnost, or economic restructuring and openness.
   Like Mazowiecki and thousands of other Solidarity activists,
Drawicz was jailed after the 1981 martial-law crackdown on
Solidarity. The Communist Party reversed itself this year and agreed
to reinstate Solidarity's legal status.
   Solidarity then scored a landslide victory in June parliamentary
elections, enabling it to form a coalition and take control of the
government.
   Drawicz has published many articles both in the state-sanctioned
and underground press about the changes taking place in the Soviet
Union under Gorbachev. He is also a translator of Russian literature.
   Urban, whom Drawicz replaces, was the chief defender of Communist
policies as government spokesman from 1981 until this year.
</TEXT>
