<FIRST>r a PM-Michelin-Uniroyal 1stLd-Writethru a0468 09-23 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Michelin-Uniroyal, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0468,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acquisition Will Make Michelin World's Largest Tire Maker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Michelin, based...', to CORRECT name of town
to Clermont-Ferrand sted Clermon-Terrand. SUBS 8th graf, `The Michelin...',
to delete redundant reference to town.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michelin Group of France agreed to acquire the
privately held Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co. in a $1.5 billion deal
that will allow the company to overtake Goodyear as the world's
largest tire maker.
   The deal announced Friday was the latest in a string of takeovers
in recent years that have put American tire brands like Firestone
and General in foreign hands.
   Michelin will pay $690 million for Uniroyal and assume $810
million in debt, company officials said.
   ``We believe this is a fine opportunity for the Uniroyal Goodrich
Tire Co.,'' said B. Charles Ames, chairman of Uniroyal Goodrich and
a principal in Clayton &amp; Dubilier, a private New York investment
firm that helped structure the deal.
   Uniroyal Goodrich will operate as a subsidiary of Michelin and
keep its headquarters in Akron. The company will continue to make
and distribute Uniroyal, BFGoodrich and other well-known brands of
tires and retain its corporate identity, Michelin spokesman Jim
Morton said.
   Michelin, based in Clermont-Ferrand, France, was locked in a
three-way contest with Akron-based Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. and
Bridgestone of Japan to be the world's largest tire company.
   If regulators in the United States and Canada approve the deal,
Michelin will surpass Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. as the world's
largest tire company, said Saul Ludwig, a tire analyst with the
Cleveland-based Raulston &amp; Co.
   The Michelin Group reported 1988 sales of $8.7 billion. Uniroyal
Goodrich had sales of $2.2 billion in 1988.
   Goodyear had sales of $10.8 billion in 1988.
   Bridgestone Corp. of Japan became the third-largest tire maker
with its $2.4 billion acquition of Firestone Tire &amp; Rubber Co. in
1987.
   Clayton &amp; Dubilier took Uniroyal private in a management-led $950
million buyout in 1985. Martin H. Dubilier, the firm's chairman,
said Uniroyal needed a partner to help finance $600 million in
improvements over the next five years to remain competitive.
   ``We saw the need in the long term for a partner,'' Dubilier
said. ``Michelin approached us. They have the resources to make us
more competitive.''
   Uniroyal Goodrich became the second-largest tire manufacturer in
North America and fifth-largest in the world when B.F. Goodrich Co.
and Uniroyal Inc. of Middlebury, Conn., merged their tire operations
in 1986.
   Last year, Pirelli S.p.A. of Italy acquired Armstrong Tire Co. of
New Haven, Conn., and in 1984, Continental Ag of West Germany bought
Akron, Ohio-based General Tire Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
