<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-SaudiArabia     09-23 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Saudi Arabia,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Denies Plotting Bombs; Hezbollah Vows Revenge For Executions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran denied today it was involved in two
bomb blasts in Mecca in July, and Tehran-supported terrorists vowed
to avenge Saudi Arabia's execution of 16 Shiite Moslems convicted of
setting the explosions.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic New Agency and Tehran Radio
quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as urging Moslems around the
world to ``break their silence over these atrocities'' by Saudi
Arabia's royal rulers.
   A statement from the fundamentalist Hezbollah said the executions
were ``a terrorist act ... The deep grudge which rules the actions
of the terrorist pagan regime ... will be a motive for avenging the
blood of the oppressed.''
   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, is the pro-Iranian umbrella group
thought to hold 16 Westerners hostage in Lebanon, including eight
Americans.
   A Pakistani man was killed and 16 other pilgrims were wounded in
the bombings on July 10 near the Grand Mosque in Mecca, Islam's
holiest city.
   Sixteen Kuwaiti nationals were beheaded Thursday for the blasts,
believed connected to an age-old feud between Sunni and Shiite
Moslems. Most Iranians are Shiites, while Saudis and other gulf
state Arabs are mainly Sunnis.
   Iran's spokesman, who was not identified, denied Saudi charges
that Iranian diplomats in Kuwait trained and equipped the terrorists
who set off explosions at the height of the Moslem pilgrimage, or
hajj.
   He said recorded confessions of the condemned men, screened by
Saudi television, were ``false allegations disseminated by the
Riyadh government.''
   Saudi Arabia said the executed men all were Kuwaiti nationals,
but most were of Iranian, Saudi or Qatari origin. Four other
defendants were sentenced to 15 and 20 years in prison and 1,000 to
1,500 whiplashes for the bombings. Another nine people were
acquitted. The rulings were made and upheld by lower and appeal
courts made up of Islamic scholars.
   The Iranian spokesman rejected confessions by the condemned men
that they were provided with explosives and timing devices by two
Iranian officers at the embassy in Kuwait, Mohammed Reza Gholoum and
Sadek Ali Reza.
   ``Those people were never employed in the Iranian Embassy in
Kuwait, and the Kuwaiti government is fully aware of this,'' the
spokesman said.
   Kuwait has not commented on the executions.
   The Iranian spokesman said the attacks were carried out by
``mercenaries working for Saudi Arabia ... to suppress Moslems who
... reject the Saudi rulers' control of the two holy shrines'' _
Mecca and Medina.
   Two years ago, he charged, Saudi Arabia pushed pilgrims ``into
blood and dust for the crime of disavowing the pagans.''
   More than 400 people, mostly Iranians, died in clashes with Saudi
security forces in Mecca in 1987.
   The disturbances were the most serious of a series of incidents
during pilgrimages since Iran's Islamic revolution in 1979, fueled
by Iranian efforts to politicize the hajj and encourage other Moslem
nations to seize shrines at Mecca and Medina from the control of the
kingdom's Saud royal family.
   After the violence, Saudi Arabia limited the number of pilgrims
and two years ago broke relations with Tehran, citing subversion and
terrorism.
   Lately, Iran's new President Hashemi Rafsanjani has indicated he
would like to mend the rift.
   The Iranian spokesman said Riyadh's accusations against Tehran
are part of a campaign by Saudi Defense Minister Prince Sultan and
Interior Minister Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz to keep relations strained.
   ``This faction strongly desires continuation of enmity,'' it said.
</TEXT>
