<FIRST>r a PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0501 09-23 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0501,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 1:50 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf bgng ``Bush, in remarks ... '' to CORRECT that
Bush urged lawyers to work for rights of the unborn in fight over abortion.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, taking a break today from
recreation and work on his United Nations speech, called on lawyers
to involve themselves in community service and ``protect the
unprotected.''
   Bush, in remarks prepared for delivery to a luncheon of the
Catholic Lawyers Guild, also urged the legal community to work for
rights of the unborn in the fight over abortion.
   ``Use your talents, your energy, and your professional resources
to reaffirm the right to life as the most fundamental freedom,'' he
said.
   The president travelled to Boston from his vacation home in
Kennebunkport, Maine, where he is spending the weekend before
heading to the United Nations on Monday.
   Hitting one of his favorite themes _ the call to community
service _ Bush told the lawyers in his speech to help the
illiterate, the homeless and others in need.
   ``I challenge you, as Catholic lawyers, not to give in to the
dismay of those today, who in the error of alarm have wandered from
the basic convictions to which our nation is pledged. I challenge
you to rekindle and foster a love of justice.''
   ``Part of your task is to use your talents _ to speak for those
unable to speak for themselves ... We must remember the
unremembered. Protect the unprotected. And stand up for those who
live in a world of pain,'' Bush said.
   At Kennebunkport, preparations for his first speech as president
to the U.N. on Monday were dominating Bush's work agenda over the
weekend, an administration official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
central part of Bush's address would be East-West relations,
including the talks that were concluding in Wyoming today between
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Officials in Wyoming said Baker and Shevardnadze reached
agreement on on-site inspections of each other's underground nuclear
test sites and on ``trial verification'' of each other's stockpiles
of long-range nuclear weapons.
   Bush met with Shevardnadze at the White House on Thursday and
received a letter from Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev on arms
control issues.
   Bush stopped on the way to Kennebunkport to stump for the GOP's
embattled gubernatorial candidate in New Jersey, Rep. Jim Courter.
   Courter is in an uphill race against Democratic Rep. James Florio
to replace the outgoing Republican Gov. Thomas Kean.
   In sharply partisan remarks, Bush told a fund-raising luncheon
the contest represents ``the future versus the past. Policies that
work versus policies that don't. A better future for our children,
or one of lost opportunity.''
   He also defended his plan to cut the capital gains tax against
Democratic charges that it would be a tax break for the rich. ``It
is a tax adjustment that is going to create jobs in America and that
is why I am going to continue to fight for it,'' said Bush.
   Before heading to his seaside compound, Bush also made a brief
stop at a remote tree farm in nearby Wells to underscore his
position on capital gains taxes, which are levied on profits from
sales of real estate, stocks and other assets.
   Farm owner Martin Morse told Bush that 1986 changes in the
capital gains tax law had cost him more than $4,000 in one year.
Morse said tree farmers must pay capital gains tax on sales of their
trees because the trees are considered tangible assets rather than
merchandise.
   Bush also squeezed in nine holes of golf before nightfall with
his national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, and fished for a
short time.
</TEXT>
