<SECOND>PM-Thatcher, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Meets Gorbachev to Discuss Arms Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Thatcher comments, CORRECTS number
of Soviets, Britons expelled to 11 sted 12 in penultimate graf. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain today
predicted success for the sweeping reform agenda of Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, saying change has gone too far to be stopped.
   ``I believe perestroika is now set on its course and will go
through to success,'' the British leader told a news conference
after four hours of talks with the Soviet president during her
one-day stopover between Tokyo and London.
   The two leaders met amid reports of a breakthrough in U.S.-Soviet
arms negotiations.
   It was their fifth meeting since Gorbachev was named Communist
Party chief in 1985. Mrs. Thatcher was the first major Western
leader to see Gorbachev since this summer's wave of strikes by
miners in the Ukraine and Siberia and flareups of ethnic violence in
Georgia, Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan.
   She expressed great confidence in the 58-year-old Kremlin leader
and his program for economic and social reforms, saying it ``opens
up vistas and horizons not available to the people of the Soviet
Union for some 70 years.''
   Asked about current domestic woes faced by Gorbachev's reform
drive, she replied, ``Anything bold and purposeful will have
difficulties to it.''
   One of the topics discussed by the leaders was arms control, and
Mrs. Thatcher said she had been ``in touch'' with President Bush on
the matter before meeting with Gorbachev at the Kremlin.
   However, she declined to comment on anything Gorbachev may have
told her on the reported dramatic swing in the Soviet position on a
superpower treaty being negotiated to slash long-range nuclear
weapons arsenals.
   Some observers said Mrs. Thatcher's good relations with Bush and
Gorbachev could help produce a breakthrough in superpower
negotiations to cut the number of long-range nuclear missiles in
half.
   But the breakthrough came in Wyoming, where Shevardnadze met
Friday and today with Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   U.S. officials said Friday the Soviet Union was dropping its
insistence on limits on the Star Wars missile defense system before
signing a treaty that would slash the number of long-range bombers,
missiles and nuclear submarines. The two sides also were reported
near agreement on inspection of each other's underground nuclear
test sites.
   Asked whether Gorbachev had mentioned the switch in the Soviet
position, Mrs. Thatcher told reporters at the Soviet Foreign
Ministry Press Center that any announcement on that subject should
be made in the United States.
   On other disarmament topics, she said she left her meeting with
Gorbachev believing East and West can reach an agreement reducing
coventional weaponry by next year. She also said prospects were
``encouraging' for a ban on chemical weapons.
   Mrs. Thatcher's personal relationship with Gorbachev is warm,
although she retains a watchful eye on Soviet military power.
   Relations between Britain and the Soviet Union slid several
months ago when the British expelled 11 Soviet journalists and
diplomats on complaints of spying and the Soviets retaliated by
expelling 11 Britons.
   But the Tass news agency said today: ``In Soviet diplomatic
circles, it is believed that these differences should not be viewed
as an obstacle to the development of relations between the two
nations.''
</TEXT>
