<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remnants of Hugo Felt Over Northeast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT that today first full day of autumn,
sted equinox, which was 9:20 p.m. Friday EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The remnants of Hurricane Hugo brought thunderstorms and gusty
winds over parts of the northeastern quarter of the nation early
today, and officials warned of flooding from Virginia to Vermont.
   Elsewhere, a cold front settled over the northern Plains,
dropping temperatures below freezing early today in some sections.
   Today marks the first full day of autumn in the Northern
Hemisphere. The autumnal equinox, the time when the sun crosses the
equator making night and day of equal length, occured at 9:20 p.m.
EDT Friday.
   Forecasters stopped tracking Hugo in Pittsburgh on Friday night
as it lost the characteristics of a tropical storm.
   Showers and thunderstorms swept across the Ohio Valley, the lower
Great Lakes and the central Appalachians.
   Earlier, Hugo blasted the Carolinas. Hurricane-force winds
pummeled coastal South Carolina around Charleston early Friday. The
storm's strength also was felt about 200 miles inland at Charlotte,
N.C., where nearly 3 inches of rain fell Friday, a city record for
the date.
   More than 2 inches of rain fell at Lexington, Ky., and more than
an inch fell at Akron, Ohio, and Erie, Pa.
   Gusty winds were reported over a large area from Virginia to New
York, with gusts of 60 mph at Snowshoe, W.Va.
   A flood watch was posted for today for much of western Virginia,
the Berkshires of Massachusetts and the northwest hills of
Connecticut. Flash flood watches were posted in Vermont and upstate
New York.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms extended across the
Tennessee Valley, the central Gulf Coast, Florida and southern
Georgia.
   Strong northwesterly winds brought cool air into the
south-central states, with high winds in the middle Mississippi
Valley.
   Light snow fell across parts of northern Wisconsin, and
temperatures hovered around freezing in South Dakota, Minnesota,
most of Wisconsin, northern and west-central Iowa and much of
eastern Nebraska.
   Out West, unseasonably warm weather prevailed with record high
temperatures reported at a number of cities. Seattle hit 91 degrees,
their latest day of 90 degree weather on record.
   Phoenix' temperature soared to a record 109 degrees on Friday,
while Tuscon sizzled at 106 degrees. It was the 90th day of
100-degree heat this year for Tuscon, a record.
   Temperature readings at 3 a.m. EDT included:
   EAST: Albany, N.Y. 75 rain; Atlanta 64 partly cloudy; Boston 77
windy; Charleston, S.C., 77 cloudy; Chattanooga 67 foggy; Cincinnati
65 foggy; Cleveland 51 rain; Detroit 47 windy; Key West 83 partly
cloudy; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New York 75 windy; Philadelphia 78
cloudy; Pittsburgh 65 showery; Portland, Maine, 68 foggy; Richmond
74 windy; Tampa 74 foggy; Washington, D.C., 76 windy.
   CENTRAL: Birmingham 63 foggy; Bismarck 28 fair; Chicago 43 fair;
Denver 53 cloudy; Des Moines 42 windy; Indianapolis 53 windy; Kansas
City 45 windy; Little Rock 59 partly cloudy; Louisville 67 rain;
Memphis 65 cloudy; Nashville 65 rain; New Orleans 66 foggy; North
Platte 34 fair; Oklahoma City 57 windy; Omaha 39 fair; Rapid City 36
fair; St. Louis 57 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 36 fair; Sault Ste.
Marie 38 showery; San Antonio 66 fair.
   WEST: Albuquerque 62 windy; Anchorage 48 rain; Boise 55 fair;
Casper 44 fair; Fairbanks 49 partly cloudy; Great Falls 57 fair;
Honolulu 78 fair; Las Vegas 67 fair; Los Angeles 65 cloudy; Medford
60 fair; Pendleton 56 fair; Phoenix 93 fair; Portland, Ore., 63
fair; Reno 57 fair; Salt Lake City 59 fair; San Diego 65 cloudy; San
Francisco 56 fair; Seattle 67 fair; Spokane 61 fair.
   CANADA: Calgary 50 fair; Montreal 72 rain; Ottawa 61 rain; Regina
34 fair; Toronto 50 windy; Winnipeg 30 fair.
</TEXT>
