<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--RitzyRails     09-23 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Ritzy Rails,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Tracking Bourgeous Bucks By Evoking Imperial Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets are making tracks to the tourist
industry by building a replica of a luxurious, turn-of-the-century
train that once ferried the nation's now-reviled aristocracy.
   Forgetting their typical disdain for the old days of czarist
Russia, the Soviets are planning a new Paris-to-Vladivostok train
that is to feature a sauna, two dining cars and roomy passenger
cars, the Tass news agency said.
   Conductors also will sport czarist-era uniforms. Dubbed the
Trans-Siberian Express, the train will be pulled by steam engines
along some stretches to enhance the historical experience.
   Tass did not say how long the trip would last or how much it
would cost. Travel time from Paris to Vladivostok is 10 to 11 days
on current trains.
</TEXT>
