<FIRST>r i PM-Belgium-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru   09-23 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Belgium-Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0513,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostage Standoff in Belgium Ends With Suicide of French Fugitive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 9th pvs, `Police said...' to FIX spelling of second reference
to Wagemans. Pickup 10th, `Delaire, who...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIEGE, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sought in France for a string of
holdups and prison escapes committed suicide today during a shootout
with police that occurred after he released three hostages, police
said.
   Police first reported they killed Philippe Delaire, 28, of France
and seriously wounded one of his Belgian accomplices, Tony Wagemans,
31, during the shootout in an apartment building. But prosecutor
Anne Bourguignont later told reporters that Delaire killed himself
during the confrontation.
   A third gunman, Belgian Edouard Delecki, 36, was arrested
unharmed.
   The shootout ended a standoff that began Sept. 16 when the three
men kidnapped a bank manager, his wife and their two daughters in
their home in Tilff, a residential southern suburb of Liege.
   The banker escaped and alerted police, who surrounded the villa.
   After a week of negotiations with policemen, the three gunmen
agreed to release their hostages for a ransom of $750,000 and an
Mercedes-Benz.
   They released the two girls, Gaelle, 10, and Francoise, 12, on
Friday and drove away with the mother, whom they later freed on the
road toward Holland.
   Two police helicopters chased the men, and all main roads and
border crossings were guarded. Spotting policemen at the border, the
three men drove back to a 28-story apartment building in Liege,
where the shootout occurred.
   Police said Delaire shot first and was killed by a bullet in the
head. The wounds of Wagemans were not described.
   Delaire, who was born in northern France, had a brief but wild
criminal career there, police said.
   Jailed for holdups, he escaped for the first time from a prison
in Lille, France, in 1985. He committed other holdups in France and
Belgium, many in the Liege area, taking hostages to cover his
escape. Arrested several times in France and Belgium, he escaped
again and again. Last year, he forced a helicopter pilot to free a
friend from a prison in Nice, southern France.
   Police said he also was sought for questioning in the killing a
20-year-old African boxer in a Liege bar in 1985.
   In several cases, police said, he molested or injured his
hostages. But no injuries were reported to his hostages In Tilff.
</TEXT>
