<DOCNO> AP890923-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FinanceMeetings 1stLd-Writethru a0410 09-23 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Finance Meetings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0410,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industrial Nations Pressing US to Cut Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS grafs 1-2 to UPDATE with start of meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance officials of the world's seven biggest
economic powers met today amid renewed calls for the Bush
administration to curb the U.S. budget deficit as its contribution
toward stabilizing world currency markets.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady and Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan hosted the private talks at the Blair House, across
the street from the White House, with their counterparts from Japan,
West Germany, Great Britain, France, Canada and Italy _ the
so-called Group of Seven.
   The finance ministers and central bankers from the seven nations
were expected to discuss their seeming failure to stabilize world
currency markets. The dollar is trading above the targets they set
despite a declaration at the officials' last meeting in April
seeking no further increase.
   A strong dollar hurts U.S. efforts to reduce its trade deficit
because it raises the price of American exports overseas and makes
foreign goods cheaper in the United States.
   The dollar's rise since the spring has come in the face of
repeated and heavy selling by the G-7 nations' central banks in an
effort to drive its value down.
   In advance of the session, the Bush administration insisted
coordination efforts had not broken down. But officials of other
nations said more was needed.
   Specifically, the U.S. must reduce the demand for dollars created
by its budget deficit, said a senior Canadian official, speaking to
reporters on condition she not be identified by name.
   ``One of the values of these meetings is peer pressure and the
need to make the U.S. repeatedly aware, the administration and
Congress, that the key to the imbalances problem is not some sort of
exchange rate policy that brings down an overly strong dollar. ...
The best way to do that is a tighter fiscal policy,'' the official
said.
   A senior official at the U.S. Treasury acknowledged, ``We all
recognize that more needs to be done. ... The United States must
reduce its budget deficit,'' but said that nations with trade
surpluses (Japan and West Germany) must stimulate consumer demand at
home so they are less dependent on export sales.
   The U.S. official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said
if the dollar were to continue its upswing ``for a lengthy period of
time, this obviously, is a matter of concern ... because obviously
we have more (trade adjustments) to accomplish.''
   Despite the talk before today's meeting, many private economists
said they were expecting little more than vague rhetoric when the
G-7 issues a communique at the end of the session.
   ``I would be shocked if anything really happened,'' said Michael
K. Evans, an economic consultant in Washington. ``But I think they
will reiterate the fact that stable currencies are better and that
they will work together to keep the fluctuations down without saying
very much about where they should go,''
   Trading in currency markets Friday seemed to reflect that
skepticism. The dollar rose in thin, erratic trading despite the
fourth straight day of Federal Reserve dollar selling. At the end of
the day in New York the dollar rose to 146.05 yen from 145.65 on
Thursday.
   The Group of Seven discussions were being held before the start
of the annual meetings of the 152-nation International Monetary Fund
and its sister lending organization, the World Bank.
   IMF officials are pushing for a doubling of the fund's resources
to allow it to better handle the crushing $1.3 trillion Third World
debt burden. A senior Treasury official said Friday the United
States had not reached a conclusion that such an increase is needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
