<DOCNO> AP890923-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-VirginIslands     09-23 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Virgin Islands,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Ravaged Islands Teetered on Anarchy, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials say FBI agents and Coast
Guard officers found anarchy on hurricane-ravaged St. Croix just
hours after the Virgin Islands' governor gave emphatic assurances
the island was peaceful.
   A Coast Guard helicopter crew that flew over the island Wednesday
morning to survey damage from Hurricane Hugo spotted bands of
looters armed with machetes and guns, a Coast Guard spokesman said.
   ``Basically there was total lawlessness from everything they
saw,'' said the spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Jeff Karonis.
   A team of five FBI agents dispatched by Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh arrived about the same time and by Wednesday afternoon
reported that ``there had been a complete breakdown of law and
order,'' said an administration official.
   The agents found ``roving bands of thugs'' looting shops and
attacking homes, the official said. Some 150 convicts who had
escaped from two prisons were also on the loose.
   Until federal agents arrived Wednesday morning, it was difficult
for officials in Washington to get information because
communications had been cut off with the storm-ravaged island.
   The accounts of FBI agents and the Coast Guard conflicted starkly
with the report the Pentagon received from Gov. Alexander Farrelly
on Tuesday night.
   ``The governor emphatically stated there was no law-and-order
problem and matters we well in hand,'' said the official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   The governor's statement was also at odds with a plea made over
ham radio earlier Tuesday night by an assistant U.S. attorney on St.
Croix, who expressed fear that looting convicts might exact revenge
on law enforcement officers and judges, the official said.
   The prosecutor's report was the basis for Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh's decision to send in the team of five FBI agents to
survey the situation, the official said.
   As that team was arriving in St. Croix on Wednesday morning, the
Justice Department established contact with the U.S. marshal for the
Virgin Islands ``who reported that there was anarchy, it was very
serious situation,'' the official said.
   As the picture of violence and lawlessness became more detailed,
Pentagon officials went to the Justice Department to develop
contingency plans for dealing with the situation.
   After consulting with the White House, Thornburgh decided to send
the FBI's hostage rescue team and the U.S. Marshals Services'
special operations group to St. Croix to protect federal officials
and property.
   At 2 p.m. or 2:30 p.m. Wednesday, Farrelly met with the senior
FBI agent in the Virgin Islands and requested a battalion of
military police to help restore order, said the official.
   A presidential proclamation was quickly drafted at the Justice
Department and orders were issued to send in military police to
restore order. Farrelly's request was reported to the White House by
the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   But the presidential order was based on a law that allows the
chief executive to send in troops without a governor's request.
   President Bush ``was relying on his own judgment based on other
reports that it was important to restore law and order,'' the
official said.
   The decision to send in troops was made after ``federal
authorities on the scene were reporting chaos, and near anarchy and
the situation as being out of control,'' Admiral William Crowe Jr.,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said last week in an
interview.
   Later Wednesday afternoon, Farrelly publicly denied that he had
asked for troops. During interviews Thursday, the governor said
reports of lawlessness and looting were exaggerated.
   He made the comments after 1,100 U.S. troops and 100 FBI and
deputy U.S. marshals had arrived in St. Croix.
   By Friday, Farrelly had ceded all law enforcement power to the
Justice Department, which now has comprehensive authority to make
arrests and conduct prosecutions for violations of both federal and
territorial law.
</TEXT>
