<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RetardedCare     09-23 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retarded Care,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocates Aim For Further Expansion of Retarded Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the mentally retarded hope a
judge has set an example for others around the country by ordering
Pennsylvania officials to seek money to restore services for
retarded Philadelphians who live at home.
   ``This decision is the first in the nation holding that people
with retardation have a right to those services,'' said David
Ferleger, attorney for an advocacy group that joined the city in
seeking the state money.
   The decision also marks the beginning of a move to state courts
instead of federal court, where Ferleger's group, the Philadelphia
Police and Fire Association for Handicapped Children, lost earlier
this year in a similar case.
   Commonwealth Court Judge James Crumlish Jr. last week gave the
Pennsylvania Department of Public Welfare until Oct. 2 to ask the
Legislature to provide the $7.56 million needed for services that
had been cut or canceled for up to 7,750 mentally retarded
Philadelphians.
   The order does not cover the Legislature, but Ferleger said if
the lawmakers turn down the request, he would ask the judge to order
the department to find the funds elsewhere in its budget.
   The judge ruled that state officials breached their
responsibility under state law to assure ``adequate mental
retardation services for all persons who need them.''
   Crumlish's opinion took state officials to task for failing to
evaluate the needs of Philadelphia's mentally retarded in coming up
with a budget. Instead, the state just added a little more to what
had been budgeted before, whether that previous amount met actual
needs.
   The ruling dealt only with the state's handling of one county.
   But ``that thing will be widely disseminated,'' said Allan
Bergman, deputy director for governmental activities for the United
Cerebral Palsy Associations.
   ``I would suggest there are other parties in other states where
they have similar grounds under their state laws,'' Bergman said.
   ``Very few states base their budgets on actual client need. That
issue will be true everywhere,'' Ferleger said.
   A 1987 survey by the Association for Retarded Citizens found
76,000 people waiting for day programs around the country.
   Richard Gold, deputy city solicitor for Philadelphia, isn't
convinced of a national effect of Crumlish's ruling. ``Our lawsuit
is under state law,'' he said simply.
   However, state law is becoming the chosen legal strategy as
groups push for services to keep people out of institutions,
integrate them into society and help them do things for themselves.
   The move to state courts began with a U.S. Supreme Court decision
in February that held the state of Wisconsin did not have a
constitutional duty to protect a boy who suffered brain damage from
repeated beatings by his father.
   Ferleger's group won an initial victory in federal court on
rights for the retarded to community services under the U.S.
Constitution. But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the
case, citing the Wisconsin ruling as grounds.
   In New Jersey, the state public advocate has sued the state
Department of Human Services in state court, contending the agency
wasn't providing appropriate community services to about 3,300
people.
   ``In recent years the federal Constitution has been interpreted
increasingly narrowly on disabilities issues. And some of the state
constitutions have been providing greater protection,'' said Linda
Headley, an attorney for the public advocate.
   Advocates like to see efforts succeed in other states.
   ``It's always important that some other judge somewhere else was
willing to do this,'' said Robert Fleischner, attorney for the
Center for Public Representation in Northampton, Mass.
   Tannis Fox, attorney for the Arizona Center for Law in the Public
Interest, said her group won a ruling by the Arizona Supreme Court
that state law required community treatment for the chronically
mentally ill.
   A national solution could come from outside the courts.
   The Senate Finance Committee in the next two weeks may consider a
bill sponsored by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., and co-sponsored by 53
others, that would eventually make such services a federal right _
the way Congress mandated in 1975 that disabled children have a
right to go to school.
</TEXT>
