<FIRST>r a AM-BridgePlunge     09-23 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Plunge,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rough Weather Halts Search For Car That Went Over Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. IGNACE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rough weather with waves up to 12 feet
high Saturday forced suspension of a search for a car that went over
a guardrail and fell from the Mackinac Bridge 170 feet into the
stormy Straits of Mackinac.
   The car was about halfway across the 5-mile-long bridge between
Upper and Lower Michigan when it apparently went out of control and
flipped over a 3{-foot guardrail Friday, state Trooper Don Tillery
said.
   The car fell about 170 feet from the bridge carrying Interstate
75 over the confluence of lakes Michigan and Huron into 170 to 190
feet of water, Tillery said.
   Witnesses disagreed on whether there were one or three people in
the car, said state Trooper Don Tillery said. No reports of missing
persons had been received Saturday, he said.
   ``People come up north to these rural cabins and (relatives)
don't expect a phone call for four or five days,'' he said. ``And a
lot of these rural cabins don't have phones.''
   The Coast Guard cutter Katmai Bay returned to St. Ignace early
Saturday after an overnight search failed to locate debris or other
evidence, Lt. John Lt. John Andrzejewski said from Sault Ste. Marie.
The Coast Guard had no immediate plans to resume the search, he said.
   ``The seas are too rough to put down any divers right now,''
Tillery said. ``We've got 6- to 12-foot waves.''
   It was the first accident of its kind on the 32-yer-old bridge,
Sgt. Kenneth Hardy said.
</TEXT>
