<FIRST>u i AM-Germany     09-23 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Genscher Denounces East German Ban of Fledgling Pro-Democracy Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's foreign minister on
Saturday denounced East Germany's ban on a dissident group, and East
Germany's former intelligence chief reportedly said he favors change
in his Communist homeland.
   The East German Interior Ministry on Thursday outlawed the
fledgling Neues Forum, pro-democracy group, saying it harbored
``anti-state'' policies. Activists say the group has grown from 30
to more than 3,000 members in two weeks.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher denounced the
East German government's action.
   ``Can it be anti-state when people want to make contributions
toward reforms of state and society? Why are they being shoved into
illegality, instead of being listened to and taken seriously?''
Genscher said in a speech in the West Germany city of Kaiserslautern.
   His speech was made available to reporters in Bonn in advance.
   Neues Forum is among a host of pro-democracy groups that has
sprung up across the country as East Germany's aging leaders
continue to reject Kremlin-style reforms despite the emigration of
thousands of East Germans to the West in recent weeks.
   Neues Forum leaders have vowed to challenge the government's
action in court.
   There have been signs of disunity over the question of reforms
within East Germany's ruling Communist Party, with some East German
officials conceding in recent days that changes are necessary.
   A West German newspaper on Saturday quoted East Germany's former
head of intellingence, Marcus Wolf, as saying ``changes are
important and belong to the huge theme of Socialist renewal.''
   The Sueddeutsche Zeiting also quoted the former spymaster, who
retired in 1987 and still lives in East Germany, as saying it is
important to ``think over the causes'' of the exodus of thousands of
East Germans to the West ``and also speak about it.''
   Wolf also said Communist East Germany stands on ``solid
foundations'' and that ``we can look into the future with
optimism,'' the newspaper reported.
   The Hamburg-based newspaper Bild am Sonntag quoted East Berlin
pastor Rainer Eppelmann, who is also a leading pro-democracy
activist, as saying many people within the East German Communist
Party favor reforms.
   Eppelman said the banning of Neues Forum is the ``futile attempt
... of a small leadership group'' within the party to ``head off
historic developments that are to come,'' the newspaper said.
   ``The Communist Party is no longer a monolithic block. The desire
for openness and change is now even driving Communist Party
members,'' Eppelmann was quoted as saying.
   Eppelmann also said the current reform movement in East Germany
is ``only the tip of the iceberg'' and will grow dramatically, the
newspaper reported.
   ``There will be more voices, and they will become more urgent,''
the Lutheran Church pastor was quoted as saying.
   Bild am Sonntag is a Sunday newspaper. It telexed copies of its
interview with Eppelmann to other news agencies in advance.
   Thousands of East Germans have been fleeing to the West in recent
years. Hungary acclerated that flood on Sept. 10, when it began
allowing thousands of vacationing East Germans unrestricted access
into Austria, where they traveled to get to West Germany.
   Since then, nearly 20,000 refugees have reached West Germany.
   Hundreds of other East Germans in Czechoslovakia and Poland have
converged on West German embassies in recent weeks, seeking asylum.
   On Saturday, Bild am Sonntag quoted unidentified diplomats as
saying that East Germany tentatively has agreed to allow its
citizens holed up inside the West German Embassy in Warsaw leave for
the West.
   In Prague, more than 100 East Germans climbed a fence to the West
Germany Embassy compound there Friday night and Saturday, bringing
to 720 the number of people in the tent encampments at the embassy.
</TEXT>
