<DOCNO> AP890923-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1521EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yeltsin     09-23 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Tells Soviets About the Wonders of America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years in the thick of the Communist Party's
struggle to build Soviet socialism, Boris N. Yeltsin says he knows a
place where the average working man is happy and secure.
   That place, he is telling his Soviet supporters, is the United
States.
   The silver-haired populist, who has spent the last two years
irritating President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the Soviet
establishment, returned from a nine-city tour of the United States
on Monday to face two pressing controversies.
   One was resolved within days when the powerful Communist Party
daily Pravda publicly apologized for reprinting an article alleging
Yeltsin boozed and spent his way across the United States.
   The other surrounds his comments about life in America,
reminiscent of tales that have drawn immigrants to the New World for
generations.
   The comments were rosier than many Americans would venture. They
are bound to be noticed by party officials who question Yeltsin's
loyalty to Communist ideals, whether he has any firm program to cure
the Soviet Union's economic ills, and wonder whether his long-term
plan is to elbow out Gorbachev.
   ``Their supermarkets have 30,000 food items,'' Yeltsin told
20,000 supporters Friday in his first public appearance since
returning. ``You can't imagine it. It makes the people feel secure.''
   In order to understand what they're missing and therefore change
their own society, Yeltsin said, ``at least 100 million Soviets must
pass through the American school of supermarkets. The leaders must
be first.''
   The 58-year-old Siberian who came to Moscow in 1985 and was named
by Gorbachev to run the capital's party organization, also cited
U.S. bounty in the popular weekly Arguments and Facts.
   The point is obvious for Soviets struggling through shortages of
items such as cigarettes, meat, matches and soap in the fifth year
of Gorbachev's reforms. Americans, Yeltsin told his supporters,
``know how to work. They enjoy life, and they are humane. They live
very well.''
   He pointed a finger at the Soviet approach to building a
socialist society:
   ``Our decades-old slogan to `Catch up with America and leave it
behind' was of great damage to us because it exists for itself, for
the sake of prestige, not for the people.
   ``We will never catch up with them and never leave them behind
and we do not need to strive for this. We must strive for a better
life for our people.'' In both his address to the crowd in
Zelenograd, outside Moscow, and his newspaper interview, Yeltsin
noted America too has its problems, primarily unemployment. But he
glanced over them.
   Yeltsin says he supports Gorbachev's restructuring program, but
differs on tactics. He says conservatives are keeping Gorbachev from
moving faster and warns Gorbachev's program is losing steam.
   He told the crowd the Soviet Union should work for more favorable
trade agreements with the United States, invite American farmers to
till Soviet land on long-term leases and allow Americans to build 1
million apartments and sell them to whoever can afford them.
   Yeltsin's barbed criticisms have not been lost on Gorbachev, who
fired him as Moscow party chief in November 1987 after he questioned
the party's policies and pace of reform.
   Yeltsin subsequently was stripped of his candidate membership of
the ruling party Politburo, but has become something of a folk hero
for his attacks on privileges for party and government officials.
   In March, Muscovites gave him 89 percent of the vote for the
capital's seat in the new Congress of People's Deputies.
   Yeltsin told the Zelenograd crowd he thought Pravda's publication
of the article alleging misconduct was an effort to help force him
off the Central Committee at an upcoming meeting.
   But Pravda itself acknowledged doubts about the accuracy of the
story it reprinted from the Italian newspaper La Repubblica, and no
such move emerged.
   However, according to Yeltsin, his criticisms did come up.
   ``At the end of the plenum, Gorbachev says, `Yeltsin returned
from America. He talks about how good it is in America, and we all
were criticized by him, including we Central Committee members and
the Presidium which I head,''' Yeltsin told the crowd.
   ``I told him, `Right, that's the way it was,''' he added.
   The crowd applauded.
</TEXT>
