<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1528EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Notification-Lawsuit     09-23 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Notification-Lawsuit,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Challenges Arkansas Abortion Notification Law in Federal Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arkansas' law requiring notification of
parents 48 hours before a minor undergoes an abortion interferes
with a doctor's right to practice medicine and a woman's right to
the operation, a lawsuit contends.
   Among the plaintiffs is a 16-year-old girl in her 11th week of
pregnancy.
   The 1989 law also assigns jurisdiction for granting exceptions to
the law to Arkansas' probate courts, which under state law have no
jurisdiction over minors, the American Civil Liberties Union alleged
in the suit filed Friday in federal court.
   The lawsuit seeks to declare the law unconstitutional, and asks
for an immediate injunction against enforcing the law. However, no
hearing date has been scheduled.
   The law was passed last spring, before the U.S. Supreme Court
ruling on July 3 that gave states more leeway on restricting
abortions through such things as banning them at public hospitals.
The high court is due to consider the constitutionality other types
of abortion restrictions in the coming term, which begins next month.
   Attorney Stephen Engstrom of Little Rock, who filed the suit
along with attorney N.M. ``Mac'' Norton of Little Rock, said he
asked Attorney General Steve Clark on Friday to allow an abortion
for the 16-year-old, identified only as Sally X.
   ``He refused. He told us to take our best shot. I think that was
insensitive,'' Engstrom said.
   The suit, filed later Friday, names Clark and the state as
defendants.
   ``I'm ready to defend this law; I believe it's constitutional,''
Clark said, adding that he did not believe the plaintiffs had tried
to use all legal procedures outlined in the law.
   Cooperating in the lawsuit is Planned Parenthood of Greater
Arkansas, which offers abortion counseling. Another plaintiff is Dr.
Curtis Stover of Little Rock, who performs abortions.
   ``Parental notice is unjustified because it increases the medical
risk to the teen-ager,'' said Nancy Libbe, a Planned Parenthood
spokeswoman.
   The lawsuit contends that the law places an undue burden on the
teen-ager's right to an abortion, and an excessive burden on either
the teen-ager or the doctor in locating both parents. There is an
exception if the whereabouts of one of the parents is unknown.
   In addition, the law is so vague that a physician could be
subject to criminal penalties, yet cannot understand what the law
requires of him, the lawsuit said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
