<FIRST>r a AM-PrintShopMassacre     09-23 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Print Shop Massacre,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Records Depict Wesbecker As Beset By Mental Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pressman who killed eight former
co-workers in a printing plant before shooting himself felt
worthless and isolated, attempted suicide before and mentioned
hurting other people, hospital records show.
   ``Here we are dealing with a man who had a long history of
chronic mental illness and chronic mental depression,'' said Dr.
Richard Greathouse, Jefferson County coroner.
   Joseph Wesbecker was ``oftentimes tortured, oftentimes seeking
help from various psychiatrists and doctors wherever he could find
it, but never really finding any peace with his treatment or any of
his psychiatric therapies.
   ``This man was tortured by what he felt,'' Greathouse said Friday.
   The records show that Wesbecker, 47, fought mental illness and
depression for the past 11 years. He was beset by racing thoughts,
sleeplessness, tremors, blurred vision, confusion, anxiety,
headaches, dizziness and anger, according to the records.
   On Sept. 14, Wesbecker fatally wounded eight people at Standard
Gravure Corp. and injured 12 with an AK-47 assault rifle before
killing himself with a pistol. Nine people remained hospitalized
Saturday.
   The records show that Wesbecker had difficulty concentrating and
once couldn't recall his own address. He felt isolated from others,
and he sometimes felt worthless.
   Wesbecker told psychiatrists he had thoughts of taking his own
life and had acted on those thoughts 12 to 15 times. He took pills,
clogged his car's exhaust pipe and tried to hang himself.
   Wesbecker, who was placed on long-term mental disability in
February, also had occasional thoughts of hurting other people, the
records indicate. He had mentioned his wife's ex-husband and his
foreman at Standard Gravure as possible targets.
   Greathouse is trying along with police to reconstruct Wesbecker's
life and illness. Under court order, Our Lady of Peace Hospital
turned over the records Friday to Greathouse, who released a summary
of the material.
   Greathouse said that:
   _Wesbecker was voluntarily admitted to hospitals at least three
times for psychiatric treatment between 1978 and 1987.
   _The hospital records reflect a man who withdrew from other
people and had difficulty with on-the-job stress, once declining a
promotion and a $4-an-hour raise because he found the job ``too
stressful and demanding.''
   _Wesbecker complained that exposure to toluene in his 17 years at
the company caused memory loss, dizziness and ``blackout spells.''
   Greathouse said the records suggested that Wesbecker posed a
threat to himself and others.
   ``I think they knew this man was quite ill mentally but were
still hopefully wishing their treatment might work,'' he said.
</TEXT>
