<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Ethnic     09-23 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ethnic,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Declares Itself Sovereign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Azerbaijan on Saturday became the latest Soviet
republic to declare itself ``sovereign,'' meaning decrees from
Moscow don't have to be obeyed if they conflict with local law,
local journalists reported.
   The vote by the Supreme Soviet parliament in the mostly Moslem
republic in the Caucasus also indirectly reasserts Azerbaijan's
right to rule Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Christian and
Armenian enclave that has belonged to Azerbaijan since the 1920s.
   Moscow put Nagorno-Karabakh under its direct administration in
February because of ethnic violence that has now lasted for 19
months. But the Azerbaijan parliament earlier this month rejected
that step as an infringement on its right to govern territory
granted it by the Soviet Constitution.
   The law on sovereignty approved Saturday by the republic's
Supreme Soviet establishes the ``integrity, indivisibility and
inviolability'' of Azerbaijan's territory, said Arif Aliev, an
independent journalist. He spoke by telephone from Baku, the
republic's capital.
   Azerbaijan also was declared ``independent'' in all matters
except those it delegates voluntarily to national authorities in
Moscow, Aliev said.
   The parliament reportedly rejected as illegal an assembly of
ethnic Armenians from Nagorno-Karabakh who in August again voted to
secede from Azerbaijan and join Armenia.
   Estonia on the Baltic Sea was the first of the 15 Soviet
republics to challenge Moscow's rule by declaring the republic
``sovereign'' last November. The Kremlin leadership immediately
rejected the move as unconstitutional, but government and Communist
Party policy have since been altered to give more powers to the
republics.
   Since President Mikhail S. Gorbachev came to power in 1985,
ethnic regions throughout their nation have increasingly asserted
their independence and embraced their nationalist heritage,
outgrowths of Gorbachev's more open society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
