<FIRST>u i AM-Quayle     09-23 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Calls for Return of Soviet-Occupied Islands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: The following was compiled from a wire service pool report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle on Saturday called for
Moscow to return several islands claimed by Japan but occupied by
the Soviets since the end of World War II.
   He also warned Japan's leading opposition party, the Socialists,
that their desire to modify a mutual security treaty with the United
States is wrong.
   The Socialists, helped by scandals and a controversial tax reform
that have eroded support for the long-governing conservatives,
currently are riding a wave of popularity in Japan.
   ``Anybody that thinks you ought to tamper or rewrite or modify
the security treaty is wrong,'' Quayle told reporters traveling with
him on Air Force II. ``It is not just a mere piece of paper. It is
an alliance, security, deterrence.''
   More than 50,000 U.S. troopers are stationed throughout Japan
under the treaty the Socialists want modified.
   The Socialists also have urged strict checks to ensure U.S. Navy
vessels calling on Japanese ports do not have nuclear weapons on
board _ a call in conflict with Washington's policy of refusing to
say whether or not its ships carry nuclear arms.
   During a visit to Japan's northernmost main island of Hokkaido,
Quayle said America shares Japan's ``heartfelt desire'' for a return
of several small islands off Hokkaido's northern shores, which Japan
calls its ``northern territories.''
   ``We hope the idea of glasnost and perestroika will someday come
to the northern territories and that they will be rightfully
returned to Japan,'' Quayle said in a speech at the official
residence of Hokkaido's Gov. Takahiro Yokomichi.
   Soviet troops occupied the islands in the closing days of World
War II in 1945, and Japanese civilians were evacuated.
   The territorial dispute has stalled completion of a treaty
formally ending the war and a visit to Japan by Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev's reforms are based on his policies of glasnost, or
openness, and perestroika, the restructing of the government and
economy.
   Quayle traveled to the Japanese Air Self Defense Force base at
Chitose, where he was briefed on Soviet military strength in the
area.
   Col. Minoru Hoso, flight group commander of the Second Air Wing,
told Quayle the Soviets have stationed one army division, or about
10,000 troops, in the disputed islands. He said they also have
400,000 troops in the region, along with 800 ships and 2,400
aircraft.
   Quayle later visited the American Misawa Air Base, on the
northern tip of Honshu, Japan's main island, where he spoke to about
1,000 military personnel and their families before returning to
Tokyo in the evening.
   He was accompanied by his wife, Marilyn, and the U.S. ambassador
to Japan, Michael Armacost, and his wife.
   Quayle arrived in Tokyo on Thursday from South Korea on the
second leg of an Asia tour that will take him to the Philippines and
Malaysia.
</TEXT>
