<FIRST>r a AM-PitBulls     09-23 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pit Bulls,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Bars City from Enforcing Pit Bull Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge barred the city from enforcing its strict
regulations of pit bull dogs, including a ban on all new pit bulls
after Oct. 1.
   In a ruling released Friday, State Supreme Court Justice Leland
DeGrasse called the Board of Health regulations irrational and
vague, saying the agency had not shown pit bull terriers were more
dangerous than other breeds.
   ``Vicious dog laws are already in place and can be enforced,'' he
said.
   City Council member Carolyn Maloney called DeGrasse's ruling ``a
resounding victory for dog owners and citizens concerned with sane
dog safety laws.'' She had opposed the regulations and submitted her
own legislation.
   The board, which enacted rules at Mayor Edward I. Koch's request,
called the pit bull ``a unique public health problem'' and cited the
dog's ``unusual savagery.''
   The American Kennel Club sued to challenge the rules, which
required the dogs to be neutered, tatooed with a registration number
and leashed and muzzled or confined at all times.
   The city argued that while pit bulls were 2 percent of the city's
dog population, they inflicted 14 percent of the bites over a
10-month period beginning November 1987.
   The name pit bull is used for several breeds, including the
Staffordshire bull terrier, the American Staffordshire terrier, the
American pit bull terrier and sometimes the bull terrier. Bred over
the centuries for dog fighting, they have powerful chest, neck and
jaw muscles.
</TEXT>
