<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Volcano     09-23 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Volcano,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mount Etna Spills More Lava, But No Danger To Inhabitants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CATANIA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke and ash billowed from Mount Etna on
Saturday but officials said there was no immediate danger from the
volcano to any nearby towns.
   The Italian news agency AGI said Europe's most active volcano
spilled lava from its southeast crater Friday night, but that the
flow came to a halt in a desert-like valley on Etna's slopes 8,700
feet above sea level.
   The mountain continued to rumble Saturday morning and coughed up
glowing material. Seismographs at the international vulcanology
institute in Catania reported tremors caused by magma movements
within the mountain.
   Although the volcano currently poses no danger to surrounding
areas, flights to and from Catania have been rerouted around Etna
because of recent volcano activity, and tourists have been forbidden
to enter those slopes deemed to be at risk.
   Meanwhile, natives and tourists alike enjoyed the fireworks
offered by one of Sicily's major tourist attractions.
</TEXT>
