<SECOND>AM-BRF--Ben's Books,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Books Written By Ben Franklin Reported Stolen From University
Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two rare books printed or written by Benjamin
Franklin and worth up to $60,000 were stolen from the University of
Pennsylvania library, police said Saturday.
   The first book, ``A Sermon on Education,'' was written by Richard
Peters and printed by Franklin in 1751. It is valued at $10,000. The
book includes a pamphlet by Franklin titled, ``An Idea of an English
School.''
   Franklin wrote the second book, ``A Log of Books to be Sold,'' in
1744. It is valued at $25,000 to $50,000.
   The books are part of a collection that is open for perusal in a
library reading room, but not available for checking out. A man
duped a library worker when he signed for the two books and five
others Aug. 16. He returned seven books, but the Franklin books were
not included.
  
