<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 1632EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolBetrayal     09-23 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Betrayal,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Shocked By Molesting Background</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents are outraged after learning
that the owner of their children's private school, arrested for
possessing child pornography, was once convicted of child molesting.
   ``It just sickens you to think that your child is in that type of
environment,'' added the mother of a 5-year-old girl who attended
the Fast Track fo Learning school in Daytona Beach.
   Parents were surprised the state does so little to monitor
private schools.
   ``If all this has happened before, why is that school there?''
asked a woman whose 6-year-old has attended Bowen's school for the
past two years. ``Why should we have to check this out? Why was it
allowed to open?''
   Parents, speaking on condition of anonymity, talked about the
school and its owner-teacher in stories published Saturday by The
Daytona Beach News-Journal and The Orlando Sentinel.
   The school's 18 students ranged from kindergarten to the fifth
grade.
   James N. and Lulu T. Bowen were arrested Thursday after
authorities searched their South Daytona home and found ``numerous
photographic items of child pornography,'' according to court
documents. Bowen, 51, and his 56-year-old wife were each charged
with 84 counts of possessing child pornography.
   Bowen was being held in lieu of $420,000 bail. Mrs. Bowen's bail
was set at $252,000.
   State Attorney John Tanner is asking parents of Fast Track
students to contact his office to determine if any of their children
are pictured in the approximately 100 photographs.
   The Bowens previously operated a day-care center in South
Daytona, but in 1984, the Department of Health and Rehabilitative
Services refused to renew the center's license because Bowen worked
there. The state claimed the couple lied on the license application
by not including his conviction. Anyone convicted of a felony cannot
work in a day-care center, according to a 1984 Florida law.
   They opened the Fast Track school in 1986.
   In 1966, Bowen had pleaded guilty to fondling a minor at a public
school in Grosse Pointe Woods, Mich. He paid a $250 fine and served
five years of probation.
   Police obtained a search warrant for the Bowens' home after a
woman reported seeing child pornography there when she went to pick
up her 7-year-old son after class.
   Because Fast Track was a private school, and not a public
day-care center, it was basically exempt from strenuous state
supervision, said Frederick J. Simpson, district counsel for the
state Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services.
   ``The problem with schools is just that they have to register
with the Department of Education, which does no investigation,'' he
said. ``There's just no regulation of private schools at all.''
   The only requirement of non-public schools in Florida is that
they comply with compulsory-attendance laws, retain student records
and meet building codes, officials said.
   In court documents, prosecutors say they are investigating the
possibility of ``assaults upon children'' by Bowen. But they
declined to elaborate on the evidence, including whether current
students have been identified in the photos or if any molestation
has been alleged.
   Parents said Bowen was the school's primary teacher, although
Mrs. Bowen occasionally helped out. Mrs. Bowen also has been working
at the City Island Library in Daytona Beach, planning exhibits and
running puppet shows for children.
</TEXT>
