<SECOND>AM-Contract Bridge,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Wins Contract Bridge Team Championship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil defeated Poland in the semfinal of
the NEC Bermuda Bowl world contract bridge team competition and then
powered past the United States in the final Saturday to win the
championship.
   Brazil beat the U.S. team with an exhibition of exceptional
bidding, declarer play and defense to score a 442-388 victory.
   Going into the Perth championship round the Americans had won
seven Bermuda Bowls going back to 1976.
   The U.S. team took the lead in the beginning but the issue had
been settled before the start of the last 32 boards with Brazil
leading at that point by 103 IMPs.
   Members of the American team, all from California, were Hugh Ross
of Oakland; Mike Lawrence of Kensington; Chip Martel of Davis; Lew
Stansby of Castro Valley; Peter Pender of San Francisco, and Kit
Woolsey of Kensington. Dan Morse of Houston was the non-playing
captain.
   In the Venice Cup world women's championship, determined Friday,
the United States successfully defended the title, defeating the
Netherlands 353-319.
