<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-History     09-23 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-History,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historical District, Buildings Battered But Not Broken By Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This 319-year-old city suffered some
damage from Hurricane Hugo to its wealth of historic buildings and
sites, but history was on its side.
   The most famous monument, Fort Sumter in Charleston Harbor,
where the first shots of the Civil War were fired, suffered about
$1 million in damage to tourist areas but was mostly intact,
according to the Interior Department.
   The National Trust for Historic Preservation, based in
Washington, will send representatives to Charleston to assess the
damage to historic buildings, Mary Hoyt, an official with the
group, said Saturday.
   The organization was worried that Hugo had dealt a major blow to
the nation's architectural history, but early reports indicated a
remarkable lack of damage, she said.
   No other city has as many historic landmarks, Ms. Hoyt said.
Charleston's historic district is home to about 2,000 buildings,
including 73 built before the Revolutionary War.
   Among them are the Drayton Hall plantation, set on a bluff over
the Ashley River, northwest of Charleston, which was built in the
1730s. The plantation house, a two-story red brick building with
white columns, suffered some water and wind damage but apparently
is structurally sound, Ms. Hoyt said.
   The city's elegant Battery district, an area of palatial
2-century-old homes that look through massive oaks draped with
Spanish moss to Charleston Harbor beyond, are still occupied by
families. A walking tour Saturday found many missing shingles and
shutters _ and countless shredded oak trees _ but the Colonial and
Georgian mansions stood unbroken.
   Broken oak trees damaged some formal gardens and blocked some
streets.
   ``We have seen lots of roof damage, lots of fallen trees and
lots of garden walls knocked down,'' said Kitty Robinson of the
Historic Charleston Foundation. ``There is a great deal of mud and
water on the first floors of some of the houses on the Battery, but
fortunately there appears to be little structural damage.''
   ``This house has been here for 269 years,'' said John McCrady,
who along with his neighbors was cleaning up Hugo's mess Saturday.
``We just lost a few slates off the roof.''
   McCrady's house was built in 1730 by William Bull, who later
became the lieutenant governor of the colony of South Carolina for
the British.
   Wayne Jordan, a history professor at Charleston College, said
most of the oldest city structures had already withstood a furious
hurricane in the late 1750s as well as the famous 1886 earthquake
that destroyed dozens of lesser buildings.
   ``The oldest buildings we have were designed to withstand
storms, and the ones that are left have been through this before,''
Jordan said. ``But I'd say there hasn't been a storm of this
magnitude for 200 years.''
   Two-foot-thick walls, raised foundations and sturdy storm
shutters all are staples of the old structures, Jordan said _
safeguards not found in newer buildings that in some cases crumbled
like matchsticks under Hugo's force.
</TEXT>
