<HEAD>Rocket Explodes in Crowded Bazaar, Killing 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket struck one of Kabul's crowded
bazaars Saturday, killing at least 11 people, hospital officials
reported.
   There have been scores of rocket attacks against the capital
this summer and the Marxist government blames them on U.S.-backed
guerrillas.
   Saturday at midafternoon when the area was bustling with
shoppers a rocket hit an ice cream vendor's shop in stalls jammed
together on the south bank of the Kabul River.
   The explosion left shreds of cloth dangling from the shattered
windows of stores around the muddy site.
   Officials at the Ebnisina Hospital said the rocket killed 11
people and wounded 19.
   However, government spokesman Mohammed Nabi Amani put the number
at 20 people killed and 45 injured. He said three rockets fell in
and around Kabul on Saturday.
   A rocket attack in the same area of bazaars Friday killed 17
people and injured 38, the hospital offficials said.
   More than 300 people have been killed and 700 wounded since June
in the rocket attacks on the capital.
   The guerrillas say they only fire at military targets and claim
the Soviet-supplied government aims rockets at its own civilians.
