<HEAD>Mother Teresa Reported Resting Comfortably</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-poverty crusader Mother Teresa, who
suffered a heart attack earlier this month, was resting comfortably
Saturday and had a good appetite, a hospital statement said.
   Doctors said earlier the chest pains she suffered for more than
two weeks had further subsided.
   The 79-year-old Roman Catholic nun was admitted to the Woodlands
Nursing Home in Calcutta on Sept. 5 with a high fever and irregular
heart beat. Three days later she suffered a heart attack.
   A hospital statement Saturday said, ``She had a good appetite
and has rested comfortably throughout the day.
   ``There has been no chest pain, but her cardiac state continued
to be closely monitored.''
   Mother Teresa's personal physician, Dr. Rajen Wats, said, ``We
will have to observe her for two more weeks before we can say if
she is out of danger.''
   Despite her poor health in recent years, the Yugoslavia-born nun
travels widely to offer care and comfort to the destitute and the
sick.
   She founded the Missionaries of Charity in 1950 to care for the
poor of this eastern Indian city's slums. The order has expanded to
3,000 nuns working in 87 countries.
   Her work earned her a Nobel Peace Prize in 1979.
