<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 2010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-23 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Rages, 14 Killed, Despite Government Peace Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government efforts to restore peace
suffered another setback with 14 people killed in ethnic strife,
military officials said Saturday.
   The officials said the latest victims, all Sinhalese, were
killed Friday. They gave no details.
   Independent sources said at least 35 people were killed in
ethnic violence in the previous 24 hours.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity as did the
military officials, said 24 people were killed in south and central
areas of this Indian Ocean nation, and 11 bodies were found in
Kandy, 55 miles northeast of Colombo. Most of the recent killings
have been blamed on Sinhalese militants waging a campaign against
the Sinhalese-controlled government.
   Justice Minister Vincent Perara told Parliament that 865 people
were killed in ethnic violence between Aug. 15 to Sept. 15.
Military officials said since Sept. 15 at least 350 more people
have been slain, raising the known death toll to 1,215 since Aug.
15.
   In its latest peace initiative, the government announced
Saturday it will include members of an extremist Sinhalese group,
the People's Liberation Front, in a multiparty committee to monitor
peace efforts in Tamil-dominated northern and eastern zones of the
country.
   Indian peacekeeping forces have been patrolling that region, but
about 600 of Insidan soldiers left for home Friday.
   It was the first Indian withdrawal since Sri Lanka and India
signed an agreement Monday stipulating that India will pull out all
of its troops by Dec. 31.
   India deployed an estimated 47,000 soldiers in July 1987 to
supervise a Sri Lankan-Indian peace accord that offered Tamil
rebels limited autonomy if they laid down their arms.
   But the largest Tamil group rejected the accord and began
fighting the Indians in a push for an independent Tamil homeland.
   The presence of Indian troops ignited a backlash by the
Sinhalese militants. They claimed the government had offered too
many concessions to the minority Tamils and compromised the
nation's sovereignty by accepting Indian soldiers to the country.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, form about 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's population of 16 million and claim discrimination by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
   The Tamil revolt and attacks by Sinhalese militants have claimed
at least 16,000 lives since the Tamil insurgency broke out in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
