<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0602-a0603-a0605-a0609 09-23 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0602-a0603-a0605-a0609,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Gorbachev to Hold Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Combines a0602, a0603, a0605, a0609; Precedes Boston; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, disclosing plans for
a 1990 summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, said
Saturday he hoped the talks would produce an agreement on arms
control.
   The president also said he was ``very pleased'' with agreements
reached by Secretary of State James A. Baker and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze during talks at Jackson Hole, Wyo.
   ``I'm very pleased with what the secretary has been able to
accomplish out there,'' the president said to reporters while
golfing at his vacation home. ``I think around the world people
will be pleased with this announcement.''
   Baker and Shevardnadze signed a chemical weapons accord and a
half-dozen other agreements aimed at lowering superpower tensions
during talks in Jackson Hole over the weekend. They also worked on
an agreement for inspection of U.S. and Soviet underground nuclear
weapons test.
   Bush took a break from golfing through a rain storm with his
national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, to receive a phone call
from Baker on the 10th hole at the Cape Arundel golf course. He
summoned reporters to tell them the news.
   The president said he hoped the summit would produce agreements
on arms control and added that ``there'll be plenty of other things
to discuss in addition to arms control.''
   Asked what he hoped to achieve in the meeting, the president
said he would be talking about achieving further arms reductions.
``There's a chance for agreement of that nature.''
   As for accomplishments during the summit, Bush said: ``A wide
array of subjects, we will be continuing to work on the arms
control agenda, it's not my view that summits must have arms
control agreements, but we're going to be working toward it.''
   The president, in a written statement released by the White
House in Kennebunkport, said: ``I envision a broad discussion of
the full agenda that the two sides have established _ human rights,
bilateral relations, arms control, regional issues and
transnational issues,''
   Bush said the summit with Gorbachev would be held late spring or
early summer most likely in Washington, which he described as
``proper for this one.'' He added: ``Undoubtedly it will be in the
United States.''
   Asked about the timing of the summit next year, he said, ``It
could be sooner but this is the agreed timetable.'' He said it
would give time for the bureaucracy to ``move forward on a lot of
fronts'' and work on a more results-oriented summit.
   Bush said there was a commitment by the Soviets to hold the
summit in the United States and that he had discussed that with
Shevardnadze when they met in the Oval Office last week.
   Bush told reporters that at the summit he would be ``going
forward in every way to achieve further arms reductions.''
   On another topic, Bush was asked whether Colombia's Monica de
Greiff, who has been the target of death threats from drug lords,
meant the drug lords were not fazed by the crackdown against them,
Bush said, ``I don't think so.''
   ``I see no reason that a single resignation will signal or lead
to or lessen'' the resolve by Colombian President Virgilio Barco to
rid his country of drug traffickers, he replied.
   Earlier in the day, Bush traveled to Boston to addressed the
annual luncheon of the Catholic Lawyers Guild of the Archdiocese of
Boston.
   He was greeted by loud, sustained cheers, whistles and applause.
He shook hands and shared the head table with Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, the Democrat he defeated to win the presidency.
</TEXT>
