<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Reforms     09-23 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Reforms,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freedom of the Press and Religion Among Proposed Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freedom of the press and religion are on the
agenda of the Soviet legislature's second session starting Monday
and debate is expected to be sharp even though many proposed
reforms have little chance of approval.
   The 4-month-old legislative session during the spring and summer
reacted to Kremlin proposals, but this time a group of 345 reform
deputies spent Saturday discussing an alternative platform. One
concept they considered was the freedom for anyone to start a
newspaper.
   The Inter-Regional Group, which includes such figures as human
rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov and maverick Communist Boris N.
Yeltsin, also proposes the open sale of paper, printing presses and
copy machines. Under the continuing system of censorship,
distribution of these items is strictly limited.
   Gavriil Popov, an economist, said the group plans to vote on its
platform Sunday.
   The legislature, or Supreme Soviet, has a formidable agenda. It
plans to act on 80 bills in 45 working days. Items include human
rights, ethnic strife and salvaging the economy.
   ``All are very important,'' deputy Sergei S. Alekseyev told a
government-sponsored news conference Friday. ``All should be
adopted.''
   But the Supreme Soviet, once a rubber-stamp body that met a few
days a year to approve the Kremlin's actions, has changed under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of restructuring and
glasnost, or openess.
   Alekseyev said there are no fewer than four versions of a new
law on the press and glasnost. One calls for a complete ban on
censorship, state-run Radio Moscow reported Friday.
   The draft platform of the Inter-Regional Group calls for the
elimination of internal passports, freedom to move in and out of
the country, access for defense lawyers to investigative reports,
public financing of parliamentary factions, the creation of
non-government television and unemployment insurance.
   But even the Inter-Regional Group does not suggest ending the
ban on private ownership of land _ a vital concept of Soviet
communism.
   Legislators also will consider bills on the right to strike, on
raising pensions, private cooperatives and taxation, said Rafik N.
Nishanov, a legislative leader and one-time Communist Party leader
of Uzbekistan.
</TEXT>
