<FIRST>u i AM-Hugo-Caribbean 2ndLd-Writethru a0596 09-23 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Caribbean, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0596,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Scramble For Water in Hugo's Aftermath</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 11-18 `Puerto Rico...$4 billion.' with 11 grafs to
UPDATE with officials saying much aid received in Virgin Islands, troops
expected to remain a week, new damage estimate; pickup graf 19 pvs `The
Justice...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Juan residents on Saturday
hauled water from swimming pools, rivers and parts of the island
unaffected by Hurricane Hugo as crews worked around the clock to
restore water and electricity.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan and a group of U.S. congressmen
arrived in Puerto Rico for a two-day fact-finding trip to Puerto
Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
   Officials say Hugo caused at least 27 deaths and billions of
dollars in damage in Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands and other
islands of the eastern Caribbean before hitting the U.S. coast on
Thursday.
   President Bush has declared both Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin
Islands disaster areas. In addition, 1,200 military police and
other troops were dispatched to St. Croix in the Virgin Islands to
halt widespread looting.
   Officials in the Virgin Islands complained that the Bush
administration was more interested in deploying troops than
airlifting relief supplies to the stricken U.S. territory.
   At a news conference here Saturday, Rep. George Miller,
D-Calif., who headed the congressional fact-finding team, was asked
why federal assistance did not start arriving in the Virgin Islands
and Puerto Rico until four or five days after the storm.
   ``That is one of the reasons we are here,'' Miller said.
   In Washington, the Defense Department said the islands had
already received relief aid including 100,000 Army field rations,
15,000 cots, four electrical generators with operating crews and
medical personnel from the 109th Evacuation Hospital of the Alabama
Army National Guard.
   It said more nonperishable food and plastic sheeting for home
repairs would also be sent.
   The Defense Department reported the Navy ship Pensacola had
arrived at St. Croix and was producing 58,600 gallons of water per
day. It said truck-mounted water purification units were being set
up in Puerto Rico to provide about 270,000 gallons of fresh water
daily.
   Virgin Islands Lt. Gov. Derek Hodge said the territory was
receiving large amounts of aid, but distribution of the supplies
was disorganized.
   He said he expected the mainland military troops to remain
another week or so.
   Puerto Rico was returning to normal, despite millions of dollars
in damage, particularly in the eastern part of the island.
   In the capital of San Juan, roads were cleared and supermarkets
and some restaurants were open. But two-thirds of the city of 1.1
million people still had no running water Saturday, and one-quarter
had no electricity, utility officials said.
   They said 70 percent of the island was without running water and
up to 35 percent without electricity.
   Utility officials said water service could be restored to San
Juan by Saturday night if work was completed as planned on
installing four electric motors to run pumps at a dam servicing the
metropolitan area. A U.S. Army C-130 flew into the capital Saturday
night with 20,000 gallons of water for distribution.
   With a steady downpour Saturday, radio station WOSO suggested
that listeners catch rainwater.
   The government was distributing water in National Guard tanker
trucks. The Department of Health advised residents to boil any
drinking water collected from other sources.
   Hodge said Friday that Hugo left homeless more than 45,000
people _ about 90 percent of St. Croix's population. St. Croix, 70
miles east of Puerto Rico, is one of the three main islands of the
group, which also includes St. Thomas and St. John.
   He said damage was tentatively estimated at $4 billion.
   However, Gerald Connolly, a Federal Emergency Management
Administration coordinator in the Virgin Islands, said Saturday his
office had made a preliminary estimate of $400 million.
   The Justice Department obtained authority Friday from Virgin
Islands Gov. Alexander Farrelly to order FBI agents and deputy U.S.
marshals to enforce all laws on the islands and to prosecute any
looters, officials said.
   There were no reports of looting Friday, but virtually every
store in Christiansted, the capital of St. Croix, appeared to have
been cleaned out in earlier looting.
   The National Guard has acknowledged that some of its members
took part in the looting, and several witnesses said some police
also were involved.
</TEXT>
