<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala-Violence     09-23 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala-Violence,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Human Rights Activist's Family Flees Guatemala</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrified by a new wave of political
violence, the family of an abducted human rights activist fled this
country Saturday after spending nearly six weeks holed up in a room
at the Red Cross.
   Maria Rumalda Camey's husband, her two babies, her brother and
his family left for Madrid under Spanish diplomatic protection.
   They were following six other relatives who were granted
political asylum by Spain last week.
   ``It is incredible how this family has been persecuted,'' Angel
Alfredo Figueroa, the deputy federal attorney general for human
rights, told The Associated Press.
   Their flight began Aug. 15, when armed men burst into the
activist's modest home in Esquintla province at 5 a.m. and dragged
her off.
   ``I heard the shots and the screams. It was her. Kidnapped,''
said her husband, Jose Gonzalo Camey, who was interviewed last week
in the crowded room where he and his family had taken refuge.
   His 23-year-old wife was the fourth person in her family to
disappear in 10 months. The others eventually turned up _ all shot
dead and dumped on roadsides. Camey, a 23-year-old farmer, doesn't
believe his wife survived either.
   Under the rightist generals who ruled in the early 1980s, tens
of thousands of Guatemalans died or disappeared, including Camey's
father. His wife has been a member of the Mutual Support Group, an
organization made up of relatives of the missing.
   Human rights groups put the toll of dead and disappeared as a
result of activities of right-wing death squads at 40,000. They say
many of the squads were linked to the army or other security forces.
   Tens of thousands of others have been displaced, fleeing the
military's scorched earth campaign against leftist guerrillas in
the countryside.
   After his wife was abducted, Camey's family and his
brother-in-law's family, fearing for their own safety, sought
refuge at Mutual Support's office in the capital of Guatemala City
30 miles away.
   About thirty minutes after they arrived, a grenade was lobbed
through the window. They were evacuated to the Red Cross, where
they remained for nearly six weeks.
   With the advent of civilian rule three years ago, human rights
abuses began to abate.
   But in the last two months, there has been a surge of killings
and bombings. Bodies have been found along the roads, their hands
cut off. Fear has returned.
   ``Guatemala is returning to the bloody times,'' Camey said,
cradling his children. ``There is terrible violence, not just in my
home, but in many homes.''
   Human rights workers blame the latest violence on right-wing
extremists who believe that President Vinicio Cerezo's rule is too
liberal. Cerezo, who has survived two coup attempts, has denied any
security forces are involved in the current violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
