<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Forestry     09-23 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Forestry,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>S.C. Forestry Commission Declares Forest Disaster Following Hurricane</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials declared a forest disaster in
South Carolina on Saturday after Hurricane Hugo left half the
state's 43 counties with extensive or moderate timber damage.
   ``It certainly is one of the worst forest disasters that South
Carolina has seen in many, many years,'' said Steve Scott, a
forester with the state Forestry Commission.
   The storm, which came ashore near Charleston packing sustained
winds of 135 mph, tore a path across South Carolina's coast early
Friday. Although its strength was dissipated once it hit land, Hugo
uprooted trees and broke limbs as it quickly moved north into North
Carolina.
   Extensive timber damage, defined as an area that will require a
great deal of salvage, occurred in nine counties on or near the
coast. Moderate timber damage _ requiring some salvage _ occurred
in 12 counties, and all the rest of the state's counties suffered
light timber damage, Scott said.
   Forestry is the third-largest manufacturing industry in South
Carolina, generating $4.3 billion annually and employing more than
30,000.
   Seventy-five state personnel were surveying damage in the
hardest-hit areas Saturday, and 35 tractors were brought in to help
salvage efforts, he said.
   Scott said he could not yet estimate the cost of the damage, and
it was still too early to develop a replanting plan or ask for
relief aid, he said.
   ``We will be working with all the private landowners in trying
to salvage the material,'' he added. ``It's going to be a big job.''
</TEXT>
