<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-Wedding     09-23 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Wedding,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whirlwind Courtship Finally Complete _ Couple Survives Wedding Obstacles</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt or AM-USAir Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nothing could stop Constance Bland and
Thomas Newberry from getting married Saturday, including the plane
crash he survived and Hurricane Hugo, which wiped out both wedding
site and honeymoon plans.
   The couple had to borrow a ring too. Theirs got lost in the mail.
   But four days of trauma ended Saturday night when the couple
exchanged their vows.
   ``This is a very special occasion in ordinary circumstances, but
it is a great occasion today,'' said Horace Hilton, the pastor
emeritus of Myrtle Grove Presbyterian Church.
   ``I honestly believe with all my heart that God spared your
life,'' Hilton told them at the altar. ``This wedding was intended
to be.''
   But it wasn't intended to be smooth.
   Newberry, a New York City banker, was on his way to Wilmington
for the wedding when his plane _ USAir flight 5050 to Charlotte _
slid into New York's East River while attempting to take off from
LaGuardia Airport on Wednesday. Two people died and 59 others were
rescued.
   The plane went down with his luggage, inside which were his
passport and tuxedo.
   Then came Hurricane Hugo, which threatened to slam into
Wilmington all day Thursday. The hurricane hit in Charleston, S.C.,
instead, but its path still managed to foul up the wedding plans.
   The couple had intended to spend part of their honeymoon in the
Virgin Islands, but the rioting and looting that followed Hugo's
path through the Caribbean gave them pause.
   ``We'll discuss it over breakfast,'' Mrs. Newberry said.
   About 100 people attended the ceremony, and some of their
friends got to help out with another last-minute problem.
   The wedding ring was lost in the mail and a new one had to be
sent from New York to Wilmington, but it arrived too late for the
ceremony.
   ``We're just lucky our friends had a ring,'' Newberry said
afterward.
   The ceremony was over at last, and most of the guests had
already gone on to the reception. The wedding party was delayed,
however, because the limousine was a half-hour late.
   ``What else can happen?'' asked the bride's father, David Bland.
``Is my car going to blow up?''
</TEXT>
