<FILEID>AP-NR-09-23-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Drugs     09-23 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Drugs,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Calls for Increased Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCCA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II called Saturday for
increased national and international efforts to fight the drug
trade but said addicts should be treated with compassion.
   ``The various public institutions, on the national and
international level, are called on to put a brake to the expansion
of the market of narcotics substances,'' the pope said during a
visit to a drug rehabilitation clinic on his three-day tour of
Tuscany in nordhern Irtaly.
   ``The interests that gain financially from such a trade must be
brought to light,'' John Paul said.
   ``Then the instruments and mechanisms they use must be
identified, and finally one will proceed to their coordinated and
efficient dismantling.''
   The pope, without mentioning any countries by name, said there
is a need to promote development in those regions where residents
depend on production of drugs for their livelihood.
   John Paul also praised the work of rehabilitation clinics and
social programs that offer addicts ``alternative models of life''
to lead them away from drugs and reintegrate them into society.
   ``Drugs are fought not only by health and judicial means but
also _ and especially _ by installing new human relationships, rich
in spiritual and tender values,'' he said.
   The pope said drug abuse is a ``clear symptom of a society that
no longer succeeds in living true values and pushes those who use
(drugs) into egoism and solitude.''
   ``In this climate, the goals to pursue become money, power,
career, consumer goods. One is ready to pay whatever price to
obtain them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
