<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-PriceGouging 1stLd-Writethru a0636 09-23 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Price Gouging, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Seeks Ordinance to Arrest Profiteers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with emergency ordinance passed,
gasoline selling for $4.50 per gallon, picks up 5th graf pvs, `Riley cited..;
INSERTS 4 grafs after 11th graf, `People bought..., to describe scene at
ice distribution centers, picks up 12th graf pvs, `The city...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council on Saturday enacted an
emergency ordinance barring price-gouging in this hurricane-ravaged
city, where 5-pound bags of ice were being sold for $10 and long
lines snaked outside stores that opened.
   ``It would be an unfair trade practice to charge something
higher than pre-hurricane prices,'' said Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr.,
who called for the emergency legislation the council passed in a
vote by telephone.
   ``If I hear of the instance of someone doing that, not only will
they be arrested, but I will personally take pleasure in
participating in the arrest,'' Riley said.
   Violators would be subjected to fines of $200 and jail terms of
30 days.
   The emergency ordinance is in effect until commerce returns to
normal, Riley said.
   Authorities reported that gas at some locations was selling for
$3 to $4.50 a gallon.
   Riley cited the instance of ice being sold for $10. The state
Emergency Operations Center requested that merchants charge no more
than $2 a bag.
   ``There is a problem with gouging,'' said John Lawson, a
spokesman for the state Emergency Preparedness Division.
   Long lines flowed from stores that managed to open Saturday,
partly because police asked that no more than 10 people be allowed
in stores at any one time. Robbie Roberts, manager of a Food Lion
grocery store in Charleston that suffered only a few damaged
ceiling tiles, said ``a couple of thousand'' customers showed up
Saturday before the store was forced to close because it had no
lights.
   Lines ``were going out the parking lot and into the street,''
Roberts said. ``It takes them about four hours to get into the
store.
   ``It was hairy at times but it worked out all right,'' Roberts
said. ``It was hot and people were irritated _ others were cutting
in line.''
   Cashiers used pocket calculators.
   People bought ``anything they could get their hands on,'' he
said. And trucks outside gave dry ice to people, he said.
   A crowd hoping to get ice in the parking lot at the Citadel Mall
started pushing and shoving and police were called, but there were
no injuries or arrests, Maj. Charles Wiley said.
   ``Frankly, some people were panicking over ice,'' Wiley said,
noting that food could begin spoiling after two days without
electricity.
   ``It wasn't a riot, but it could have been,'' said Police Lt.
Mike Connolly, one of the first officers on the scene. ``There was
some pushing and shoving, cursing, just some hot tempers.''
   At another mall, motorists turned one lane of a road into a
parking lot when they jumped out of their cars to get ice that was
being given out.
   The city has been without electricity since Thursday, when
Hurricane Hugo toppled power lines in much of the state, leaving
hundreds of thousands of people without power.
   Restoring electricity ``may take a very long time,'' Riley said.
``There's no electricity coming into the transmission lines and the
generating capacity down here is gone.''
   Utility crews from Georgia, Alabama and Florida have been sent
to South Carolina to help, he said.
   Riley said the city surveyed 2,000 buildings, one-third the
total in Charleston, and found 24 in varying degrees of collapse.
He said there also were a number of collapsed chimneys in danger of
sliding off sloped roofs and ``extraordinary'' tree damage in the
city.
   Despite the difficulties, the mayor said he was inspired by the
spirit in which Charleston residents endured the hardships.
   ``Throughout the city today, people are upbeat and they are
thankful,'' he said. ``They're thankful they're alive and that the
city is essentially intact.''
   The American Red Cross expects Hurricane Hugo relief efforts to
be the costliest in the organization's history, a spokesman said
Saturday.
   Dave Langston, assistant director of Eastern Relief Operations
of the Red Cross, said the storm will cost the agency an estimated
$38 million.
   ``We estimate that more than 73,000 people have received
assistance to date, and this is just the beginning,'' Langston said
at a news conference.
   More than 150 volunteers and paid disaster specialists will be
brought into Carolinas and other affected areas, he said.
</TEXT>
