<FIRST>u a AM-BusAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0606 09-23 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0606,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Families, Friends Mourn Loss of 15 Youngsters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with truck driver refusing to
answer questions, brakes apparently working, CORRECTS to show that 81 were
on board bus; CORRECTS spellings of hospital spokeswoman Alvarez and priest
Francisco Quezada; includes Coca-Cola company offering to pay for victim
expenses. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Many who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of a truck that collided with a
school bus and knocked it into a water-filled pit refused Saturday
to answer questions about the accident that killed 20 teen-agers,
an accident investigator said.
   Also Saturday, Lee Dickinson of the National Transportation
Safety Board said an examination of the truck's braking system
found ``the brakes did work.'' The truck driver had told police
after Thursday's accident that the brakes failed.
   On the advice of his attorneys, Ruben Perez, 25, chose not to
talk to NTSB board members who are investigating the accident that
injured at least 63 others, Dickinson said. Perez's refusal will
not hinder the federal probe, he added.
   An examination of the brakes found they were working, he said,
but added that they were not perfectly adjusted. The truck passed
state inspection last month, Dickinson said.
   There were 81 aboard the bus when the accident occurred and the
vehicle had a capacity of 83, Dickinson said.
   Investigators planned Sunday to question the driver of the bus,
Gilberto Pena, who was in stable condition Saturday night at
Mission General Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Estella Alvarez.
   One student still was listed in critical condition in Mission
General's intensive care unit on Saturday.
   Valley Coca-Cola Bottling Company Inc., the owner of the truck
that rammed the school bus, offered Saturday ``to pay all medical
and funeral expenses of the families involved in Thursday's tragic
bus accident,'' according to a statement issued by Dan Fairley,
manager of the McAllen-based company.
   Earlier Saturday, funerals were held for 15 of the 20 teen-agers
who died in the accident.
   ``If you want to shout, shout. If you want to cry, cry,'' the
Rev. Francisco Quezada told 4,000 people who crowded a funeral for
four of the victims. ``If you want to strike your chest, those are
all natural human reactions, but we need to transform the shouts
and cheers into hope.''
   The multitude, many of them standing, packed the San Juan del
Valle cathedral for the funerals of Marta Lozano, 13, Carmen
Canales, 16, Veronica Perez, 14, and her cousin Yesenia Perez, 15.
   Many who attended the Mass at San Juan del Valle, about 15 miles
from this border town of 3,700, did not know the girls but said
they felt like they had lost some neighbors.
   Rosie Gutierrez, 25, of McAllen, said she attended because ``it
felt like it was part of us. It felt like it was part of my
family.''
   Quezada asked the mourners ``not to wait for another tragedy for
the opportunity to be close and loving to each other.''
   Mariachi musicians played religious songs for the bilingual Mass.
   At another crowded Mass at St. Paul's Catholic Church in nearby
Mission, about 400 family members and friends remembered Michael
Saenz, 14, and his brother, David, 12.
   Michael had escaped moments after the bus plunged into a
water-filled pit, but died while trying to save his younger brother
and others trapped in the submerged bus.
   The Rev. Jerry Frank said the bus tragedy was not God's will,
but he asked God to help the community to accept the deaths of the
20 young people.
   ``We all know that something is terribly wrong and it just ain't
right that this terrible tragedy had to happen,'' Frank said. ``It
just doesn't fit when the young people die and they carry their
future with them before the Lord.''
   A steady stream of curious Valley residents continued to drive
past the accident site Saturday. Some parked their cars and got out
to look at the pit.
   ``I have kids and I wouldn't like for my kids to go in the bus
and have this happen,'' Evangelina Churbe of Pharr said, standing
with her four children. ``It would drive me crazy if one of my kids
would drown.''
</TEXT>
